WEBVTT

00:37.996 --> 00:39.623
MAN:
<i>That's right.</i>

00:40.290 --> 00:41.917
<i>New York.</i>

00:42.251 --> 00:44.925
<i>It's 1958.</i>

00:45.796 --> 00:49.300
<i>Anyway, for a few more minutes it is.</i>

00:49.508 --> 00:53.263
<i>Come midnight, it's gonna be 1959.</i>

00:53.470 --> 00:57.475
<i>A whole other feeling. The new year.</i>

00:58.100 --> 00:59.602
<i>The future.</i>

01:00.769 --> 01:05.275
<i>Yeah, Old Daddy Earth fixing to start</i>
<i>one more trip around the sun.</i>

01:05.482 --> 01:09.328
<i>Everybody hoping this ride round</i>
<i>be a little more giddy...</i>

01:09.528 --> 01:11.576
<i>...a little more gay.</i>

01:11.780 --> 01:16.160
<i>Yup, all over town,</i>
<i>champagne corks is a-popping.</i>

01:16.368 --> 01:22.375
<i>Over in the Waldorf, the big shots is</i>
<i>dancing to the strains of Guy Lombardo.</i>

01:22.583 --> 01:28.556
<i>In Times square, the little folks is watching</i>
<i>and waiting for that big ball to drop.</i>

01:29.172 --> 01:33.222
<i>They're all trying to catch hold</i>
<i>of one moment of time...</i>

01:33.427 --> 01:39.400
<i>...to be able to say,</i>
<i>"Right now! This is it! I got it!"</i>

01:39.600 --> 01:41.022
[CHUCKLES]

01:41.226 --> 01:43.649
<i>Of course, by then it'll be past.</i>

01:43.854 --> 01:49.281
<i>But they're all happy,</i>
<i>everybody having a good time.</i>

01:49.484 --> 01:52.203
<i>Well, almost everybody.</i>

01:52.404 --> 01:56.500
<i>There's a few lost souls</i>
<i>floating around out there.</i>

01:58.035 --> 02:00.538
<i>Now, if you all ain't from the city...</i>

02:00.746 --> 02:04.250
<i>...we got something here</i>
<i>called "the rat race. "</i>

02:04.458 --> 02:08.758
<i>Got a way of chewing folks up</i>
<i>so that they don't want no celebrating...</i>

02:08.961 --> 02:11.135
<i>...don't want no cheering up.</i>

02:11.340 --> 02:14.014
<i>Don't care nothing about no New Year's.</i>

02:14.676 --> 02:19.728
<i>Out of hope, out of rope, out of time.</i>

02:20.599 --> 02:23.603
<i>This here is Norville Barnes.</i>

02:24.561 --> 02:26.438
<i>That office he's stepping out of...</i>

02:26.647 --> 02:30.322
<i>...is the office of the president</i>
<i>of Hudsucker Industries.</i>

02:30.525 --> 02:32.448
<i>That's his office.</i>

02:33.403 --> 02:35.826
<i>How'd he get so high?</i>

02:36.031 --> 02:39.035
<i>And why's he feeling so low?</i>

02:39.868 --> 02:42.212
<i>Is he really going to do it?</i>

02:42.412 --> 02:46.588
<i>Is Norville really gonna</i>
<i>jelly up the sidewalk?</i>

02:47.417 --> 02:52.298
<i>Well, the future, that's something</i>
<i>you can never tell about.</i>

02:53.090 --> 02:56.469
<i>But the past, heh-heh...</i>

02:56.760 --> 02:59.559
<i>...that's another story.</i>

04:12.502 --> 04:14.425
[BUZZER SOUNDS]

05:15.899 --> 05:17.446
[BUZZER SOUNDS]

05:21.530 --> 05:23.658
In the third quarter
we saw no signs of weakening.

05:23.865 --> 05:26.960
We're up 18 percent over last year's
third-quarter gross...

05:27.160 --> 05:29.583
...and that, needless to say,
is a new record.

05:29.788 --> 05:34.385
Our competition continues to flag
and we continue to take up the slack.

05:34.584 --> 05:37.212
Market shares in most divisions
is increasing...

05:37.420 --> 05:40.720
...and we have opened
seven new regional offices.

05:40.924 --> 05:42.301
Our international division...

05:42.509 --> 05:46.639
...is also showing vigorous signs of upward
movement for the last six months...

05:46.847 --> 05:50.147
...and we're looking
at some exciting things in R&D.

06:30.307 --> 06:33.811
Sub-franchising.
Don't talk to me about sub-franchising.

06:34.019 --> 06:36.272
We're making so much money
in sub-franchising...

06:36.479 --> 06:38.152
...it isn't even funny.

06:38.356 --> 06:42.361
Our nominees and assigns
continue to multiply and expand...

06:42.569 --> 06:46.199
...extending our influence nationally
and abroad.

06:46.406 --> 06:48.704
Our owned
and operateds are performing...

06:48.909 --> 06:52.163
...far beyond our expectations
both here and abroad.

06:52.370 --> 06:54.919
And the Federal Tax Act of 1958...

06:55.123 --> 06:59.799
...is giving us a swell write-off
on our plant and heavies.

07:24.277 --> 07:28.373
And our last debenture issue
was this year's fastest seller.

07:28.573 --> 07:31.292
So third quarter and year-to-date...

07:31.493 --> 07:35.293
...we have set a new record in sales,
a new record in gross...

07:35.497 --> 07:38.171
...a new record in pre-tax earnings...

07:38.375 --> 07:41.470
...a new record in after-tax profits...

07:41.670 --> 07:44.549
...and our stock has split twice
in the past year.

07:44.756 --> 07:46.133
In short...

07:46.341 --> 07:47.843
[WATCH WINDING]

07:50.637 --> 07:52.514
...we're loaded.

07:52.722 --> 07:54.645
[ALL CHUCKLING]

07:54.849 --> 07:56.021
[TICKING]

07:59.813 --> 08:00.860
[CLEARS THROAT]

08:44.691 --> 08:46.364
Mr. Hudsucker?

08:46.568 --> 08:48.366
[CAR HORN HONKS]

09:11.843 --> 09:13.470
[SCREAMING]

09:41.790 --> 09:43.918
[SCREAMING]

09:44.125 --> 09:46.093
[BELL TOLLING]

10:31.923 --> 10:35.268
It's a pity to waste a whole Montecristo.

10:35.468 --> 10:36.845
He could've opened the window.

10:37.053 --> 10:39.772
Waring Hudsucker never did anything
the easy way.

10:39.973 --> 10:44.023
Why? Why did he do it?
Everything was going so well.

10:44.227 --> 10:47.106
What, am I a headshrinker?
Maybe the man was unhappy.

10:47.313 --> 10:49.156
[SOBBING]
He didn't look unhappy.

10:49.357 --> 10:53.828
- He didn't look rich.
- He was never an easy man to figure out.

10:54.028 --> 10:56.747
He built this company
with his bare hands.

10:56.948 --> 10:59.918
Every step he took was a step up...

11:00.243 --> 11:01.995
...except, of course, this last one.

11:02.203 --> 11:04.331
Sure, sure he was a swell fella...

11:04.539 --> 11:06.837
...but when the president,
chairman of the board...

11:07.000 --> 11:10.345
...and owner of 87 percent
of the company stock drops...

11:10.879 --> 11:12.802
- ...44 floors...
- Forty-five.

11:13.006 --> 11:14.223
Counting the mezzanine.

11:14.424 --> 11:17.143
Then the company, too,
has a problem. Stillson!

11:19.345 --> 11:21.939
What exactly is the disposition
of Waring's stock?

11:22.140 --> 11:23.562
Well, as you know...

11:23.766 --> 11:25.643
...Hud left no will and no family.

11:25.852 --> 11:28.731
The company bylaws
are quite clear in that event.

11:28.938 --> 11:32.363
"His entire portfolio will be converted
into common stock...

11:32.567 --> 11:36.913
...and will be sold over the counter
as of the first of the fiscal year...

11:37.113 --> 11:39.411
- ...following his demise."
- Meaning?

11:39.616 --> 11:43.120
Meaning simply that Waring's stock
and control of the company...

11:43.328 --> 11:46.798
...will be made available
to the public January 1st.

11:48.291 --> 11:49.668
Do you mean to say...

11:49.876 --> 11:53.506
...that any slob in a smelly T-shirt
will be able to buy Hudsucker stock?

11:54.130 --> 11:55.723
The company bylaws are quite clear.

11:55.924 --> 11:57.847
My God! You're animals!

11:58.051 --> 12:02.272
How can you discuss his stock
when the man has just leapt 45 floors?

12:02.472 --> 12:05.021
- Forty four.
- Not counting the mezzanine.

12:05.225 --> 12:07.273
Quit showboating, Addison.
The man is gone.

12:07.477 --> 12:10.651
The question now is whether
we'll let John Q. Public waltz in here...

12:10.855 --> 12:13.825
- ...and buy our company.
- What are you suggesting, Sydney?

12:14.025 --> 12:17.120
Certainly we can't afford
to buy a controlling interest.

12:17.320 --> 12:19.618
Not while the stock is this strong.

12:20.406 --> 12:22.909
How soon before Hud's paper
hits the market?

12:23.117 --> 12:24.289
- January 1st.
- Thirty days.

12:24.494 --> 12:26.167
- Four weeks.
- A month at the most.

12:26.371 --> 12:29.500
One month to make the blue-chip
investment of the century...

12:29.707 --> 12:32.085
...look like a round-trip ticket
on the <i>Titanic</i>.

12:32.293 --> 12:34.546
We play up the fact that Hud is dead.

12:34.754 --> 12:36.427
ALL:
Long live the Hud!

12:36.631 --> 12:39.601
- We depress the stock.
- To the point where we can buy 50 percent.

12:39.801 --> 12:41.803
- Fifty one.
- Not counting the mezzanine.

12:42.011 --> 12:43.388
- It could work.
- It should work.

12:43.596 --> 12:46.224
- It would work.
- It's working already.

12:47.433 --> 12:51.279
Waring Hudsucker is abstract art
on Madison Avenue.

12:51.479 --> 12:55.985
What we need now is a new president
who will inspire panic in the stockholder.

12:56.192 --> 12:57.489
- A puppet.
- A proxy.

12:57.694 --> 12:59.116
MAN:
A pawn.

12:59.320 --> 13:02.574
Sure, sure, some jerk...

13:02.782 --> 13:05.160
...we can really push around.

13:06.577 --> 13:10.047
You punch in at 8:30 every morning,
at 7:30 following a business holiday...

13:10.248 --> 13:12.501
...unless it's a Monday,
then you punch in 8:00.

13:12.709 --> 13:15.929
- Punch in late and they dock you.
MAN: This goes to seven! Urgent.

13:16.129 --> 13:19.724
Incoming articles get a voucher.
Outgoing articles provide a voucher.

13:19.924 --> 13:22.347
Move any article without a voucher
and they dock you!

13:22.552 --> 13:24.975
Take this up to the secretarial pool
on three! ASAP!

13:25.179 --> 13:27.898
Letter-size, a green voucher!
Folder-size, a yellow voucher!

13:28.099 --> 13:31.319
- Parcel-size, a maroon voucher!
- This is for Morgatross! Chop-chop!

13:31.519 --> 13:34.523
Wrong color voucher and they dock you!

13:34.731 --> 13:37.109
6-7-8-7-0-4-9-Alpha-6!

13:37.317 --> 13:40.491
That is your employee number!
It will not be repeated!

13:40.695 --> 13:43.323
Without your employee number
you cannot get your paycheck.

13:43.531 --> 13:44.874
All right, this goes up to 27!

13:45.074 --> 13:47.873
Return a waiver!
Do not return without a signed waiver!

13:48.077 --> 13:52.298
Inter-office mail is code 37!
Intra-office mail is 37-3.

13:52.498 --> 13:54.671
Outside mail is 3-37.

13:54.876 --> 13:56.469
Code it wrong and they dock you!

13:56.669 --> 13:59.639
I was supposed to have this
on 2810 minutes ago!

13:59.839 --> 14:01.261
This has been your orientation.

14:01.466 --> 14:04.470
Is there anything you do not understand
or understand partially?

14:04.677 --> 14:08.352
If you have not been fully orientated,
you must file a complaint with Personnel!

14:08.556 --> 14:11.400
File a faulty complaint
and they dock you!

14:11.601 --> 14:14.070
[WHISTLING]

14:16.814 --> 14:20.739
Kloppitt. Kloppitt, Kloppitt...

14:20.943 --> 14:22.320
Max Kloppitt.

14:22.528 --> 14:24.656
"Max Kloppitt, Jr."

14:33.623 --> 14:36.752
What do you do when the envelope
is too big for the slot?

14:36.959 --> 14:40.213
Well, if you fold them, they fire you.

14:42.548 --> 14:44.676
I usually throw them out.

14:50.556 --> 14:52.900
- Just got hired today.
OLD MAN: Mm-hm.

14:53.101 --> 14:55.695
- Terrific.
NORVILLE: You know, entry level.

14:55.895 --> 14:57.613
OLD MAN:
Tell me about it.

14:58.439 --> 15:01.409
But I got big ideas.

15:02.151 --> 15:03.698
I'm sure you do.

15:03.903 --> 15:07.749
For instance,
take a look at this sweet baby.

15:11.619 --> 15:12.962
I developed it myself.

15:13.162 --> 15:15.790
Yes, sirree, this is my ticket upstairs.

15:19.168 --> 15:20.966
You know, for kids.

15:21.671 --> 15:23.264
Terrific.

15:23.756 --> 15:26.475
So you see, I won't be working
in the mail room long.

15:26.676 --> 15:29.771
No, I don't guess you will be.

15:29.971 --> 15:32.941
- How long you been here?
- Forty-eight years.

15:33.433 --> 15:37.813
Next year they move me up to parcels
if I'm lucky.

15:38.020 --> 15:40.114
MAN [ON PA]:
<i>Attention Hudsucker employees!</i>

15:40.314 --> 15:42.487
<i>Attention Hudsucker employees!</i>

15:42.692 --> 15:46.413
<i>We regretfully announce</i>
<i>that at 30 seconds after the hour of noon...</i>

15:46.612 --> 15:47.704
<i>...Hudsucker time...</i>

15:47.905 --> 15:50.658
<i>...Waring Hudsucker,</i>
<i>founder, president...</i>

15:50.867 --> 15:53.666
<i>...and chairman of the</i>
<i>board of Hudsucker Industries...</i>

15:53.870 --> 15:55.213
<i>...merged with the infinite.</i>

15:55.413 --> 15:58.383
<i>To mark this occasion of corporate loss...</i>

15:58.583 --> 16:03.134
<i>...we ask that all employees observe</i>
<i>a moment of silent contemplation.</i>

16:07.300 --> 16:08.472
[EMPLOYEE COUGHS]

16:09.427 --> 16:11.475
MAN [ON PA]:
<i>Thank you for your kind attention.</i>

16:11.679 --> 16:14.523
<i>This moment has been duly noted</i>
<i>on your timecards...</i>

16:14.724 --> 16:18.194
<i>...and will be deducted from your pay.</i>
<i>That is all.</i>

16:18.394 --> 16:19.816
[ALARMS WAILING]

16:21.314 --> 16:23.863
- Blue letter!
- Blue letter!

16:24.066 --> 16:25.784
They're bringing down a blue letter!

16:59.894 --> 17:01.487
OLD MAN:
It's a blue letter.

17:02.063 --> 17:03.861
Top, top level.

17:04.065 --> 17:06.739
Confidential communication
between the brass.

17:07.401 --> 17:09.574
Usually bad news.

17:09.779 --> 17:11.906
They hate blue letters upstairs.

17:15.826 --> 17:18.124
- Hate them.
- You!

17:18.329 --> 17:21.458
Yeah, you! Barnes!
You don't look busy!

17:22.124 --> 17:24.343
Think you can handle a blue letter?

17:24.544 --> 17:27.218
This letter was sent this morning
by the big man himself...

17:27.421 --> 17:29.014
...that's right, Waring Hudsucker!

17:29.215 --> 17:32.765
It's addressed to Sid Mussburger,
Hudsucker's right-hand man!

17:32.969 --> 17:34.516
It's a blue letter!

17:34.887 --> 17:37.936
That means you got to put it
right in Mussburger's hands.

17:38.140 --> 17:40.359
No secretaries! No receptionists!

17:40.560 --> 17:43.530
No colleagues! No excuses!

17:43.729 --> 17:45.231
Mussburger!

17:46.816 --> 17:51.117
Hi, my name's Buzz, I got the fuzz,
I make the elevator do what she does.

17:51.779 --> 17:54.328
Hang it up to dry.
What's your pleasure, buddy?

17:54.532 --> 17:57.251
- Forty-four.
- Forty-four, the top-brass floor.

17:57.451 --> 18:00.204
Say, buddy, what takes
50 years to get to the top floor...

18:00.413 --> 18:02.165
...and 30 seconds to get down?

18:02.373 --> 18:04.717
Waring Hudsucker! You get it, buddy?

18:04.917 --> 18:08.421
Say, buddy! Mr. Kline, up to nine.
Mrs. Dell, Personnel.

18:08.629 --> 18:10.302
- Mr. Levin, 37.
- Thirty-six.

18:10.506 --> 18:13.180
Walk down! Ladies and gentlemen,
please step to the rear.

18:13.384 --> 18:16.638
- Here comes the gargantuan Mr. Grier.
- Buzz.

18:17.847 --> 18:20.771
Say, buddy, who's the most liquid
businessman on the street?

18:21.350 --> 18:23.227
Waring Hudsucker. Say, buddy.

18:23.436 --> 18:27.486
When is the sidewalk fully dressed?
When it's wearing Hudsucker! Ha-ha-ha.

18:28.316 --> 18:30.694
You get it, buddy?
It's a pun, it's a knee-slapper...

18:30.901 --> 18:34.155
...it's a play on... Jesus, Joseph and Mary,
is that a blue letter?

18:34.363 --> 18:39.460
Why didn't you tell a guy? Hold on, folks,
we're express to the top floor!

18:39.660 --> 18:40.877
[ELEVATOR WHIRRING]

18:41.746 --> 18:43.214
[ELEVATOR BELL DINGS]

18:54.050 --> 18:55.768
Good luck, buddy.

18:58.638 --> 19:00.686
You're gonna need it. Ha-ha-ha.

19:01.057 --> 19:03.025
[SCRAPING]

19:11.734 --> 19:12.701
[CLEARS THROAT]

19:12.902 --> 19:14.495
Mr. Mussburger's office?

20:10.042 --> 20:11.635
[CLEARS THROAT]

20:12.461 --> 20:13.758
[IN SOFT VOICE]
Hello.

20:13.963 --> 20:17.718
- Do you have an appointment?
- No.

20:17.925 --> 20:22.021
- Shall we look in the book? Hmm?
- Ma'am, we shall...

20:22.221 --> 20:25.270
- We don't seem to be in the book.
- I wouldn't be.

20:25.474 --> 20:29.445
If we had an appointment,
we'd be in the book.

20:29.645 --> 20:31.192
[PANTING]
I have this, uh...

20:31.397 --> 20:32.523
Oh, here it is. Heh.

20:33.482 --> 20:35.280
[SCREAMING]

20:38.195 --> 20:39.913
MUSSBURGER:
Gambotz?

20:40.114 --> 20:41.457
Harry Gambotz?

20:41.657 --> 20:45.036
No, too risky.
He's green but he's not slow.

20:45.786 --> 20:46.958
Who is he?

20:47.163 --> 20:50.007
No, I want an imbecile, not a cipher
or you'd have the job.

20:51.167 --> 20:52.168
Nuh-nuh.

20:52.376 --> 20:54.470
They moved him to grommets
and O-rings.

20:54.670 --> 20:56.138
He's doing pretty well.

20:57.089 --> 20:59.638
No, no, not, McClanahan.

20:59.842 --> 21:02.891
He bungled the Teleyard merger,
thinks he's got something to prove.

21:03.095 --> 21:04.847
Who let you in?

21:05.055 --> 21:08.650
Atwater? Tremendous.
Except I just fired him last week.

21:08.851 --> 21:10.228
WOMAN [OVER INTERCOM]:
<i>Mr. Mussburger...</i>

21:10.436 --> 21:11.904
<i>...Mr. Bumstead's waiting downstairs.</i>

21:12.104 --> 21:14.198
- I'll be right there.
WOMAN: <i>Yes, Mr. Mussburger.</i>

21:14.398 --> 21:15.490
Spit it out!

21:15.691 --> 21:17.568
- I, uh...
- Yeah?

21:17.777 --> 21:20.200
Well, maybe you're
the company's biggest moron.

21:20.404 --> 21:24.034
We can't use Morris. Been here too long.
He's a nice guy with too many friends.

21:24.241 --> 21:27.495
In fact, why don't you fire him?
Scratch that, I'll fire him.

21:27.703 --> 21:29.455
Make it fast, huh, fast!

21:29.663 --> 21:31.540
WOMAN [OVER INTERCOM]:
<i>Mr. Bumstead is growing restless.</i>

21:31.749 --> 21:33.922
MUSSBURGER: Tell him I'll be right there.
Give him a magazine.

21:34.126 --> 21:35.548
What, are you a mute?

21:35.753 --> 21:37.175
[PHONE RINGS]

21:37.505 --> 21:39.553
How's the stock doing? Bad?

21:39.757 --> 21:42.681
Well, it's not bad enough.
Listen, chump.

21:42.885 --> 21:46.935
Either you find me a ding-dong or tender
your key to the executive washroom.

21:47.139 --> 21:50.689
That goes double for you, pal.
Ear-clay? Ood-gay!

21:54.897 --> 21:57.525
This better be good. I'm in a bad mood.

21:58.484 --> 22:01.784
Sir, I've got something for you
from the mail room, but first...

22:01.987 --> 22:06.959
...if I could take a minute of your very
valuable time to show you something...

22:07.159 --> 22:10.333
...I've been working on
for the past two or three years.

22:11.080 --> 22:12.753
[METAL BALLS STRIKING]

22:17.378 --> 22:18.721
You know, for kids.

22:19.713 --> 22:22.637
It's perfect for Hudsucker,
not that I'm any great genius.

22:22.842 --> 22:25.061
They say inspiration
is 99 percent perspiration...

22:25.261 --> 22:27.138
...in my case
it's at least twice that...

22:27.346 --> 22:30.065
- ...but I've got to tell you, this sweet...
- Wait a minute!

22:38.399 --> 22:39.776
Huh.

22:56.458 --> 22:57.926
Hmm.

23:14.643 --> 23:16.361
Sit down, son.

23:18.647 --> 23:20.115
Go ahead.

23:21.692 --> 23:23.239
Try it on.

23:36.332 --> 23:37.299
Put your feet up.

23:41.462 --> 23:42.554
Go ahead.

23:44.757 --> 23:48.136
Let's get to know one another, shall we?

23:49.011 --> 23:50.638
Let's chat.

23:53.599 --> 23:54.600
Man-to-man.

23:58.479 --> 24:04.236
Now then,
you're from the basement, aren't you?

24:05.444 --> 24:08.368
And weren't blessed with much...

24:09.698 --> 24:10.995
...education?

24:11.367 --> 24:13.995
Well, I am a college graduate.

24:14.203 --> 24:16.626
But you did not excel in your studies.

24:16.830 --> 24:19.504
- Well, I... I made Dean's List.
- Oh.

24:19.708 --> 24:21.927
At the Muncie College
of Business Administration.

24:22.127 --> 24:23.504
[CHUCKLES]

24:23.712 --> 24:26.807
And your friends, they called you "jerk,"
didn't they?

24:27.007 --> 24:28.054
Mm, unh-uhn.

24:28.258 --> 24:30.135
- "Dope?" "Dipstick?"
- Mm-mm. No.

24:30.344 --> 24:32.847
"Lamebrain?" "Schmo?"
Not even behind your back?

24:33.055 --> 24:35.854
Well, as a matter they voted me
"Most Likely to Succeed."

24:36.058 --> 24:37.310
You're fired.

24:37.518 --> 24:39.065
[BOTH GRUNTING]

24:39.269 --> 24:43.024
Get your feet off my desk,
get out of my office.

24:43.232 --> 24:45.155
Leave your apron in the locker room.

24:45.359 --> 24:46.360
Oh, my God!

24:46.568 --> 24:50.948
The Bumstead contract. I've been
working on that deal for four years!

24:51.156 --> 24:53.204
Get out of here!
I'll take care of it! Get out.

24:54.034 --> 24:57.129
You could have destroyed
the most sensitive document of my career.

24:57.329 --> 24:59.752
WOMAN: <i>Mr. Bumstead</i>
<i>is threatening to leave the building.</i>

24:59.957 --> 25:01.083
I'm on my way down.

25:01.291 --> 25:03.885
We need the first page
of the contract retyped.

25:04.086 --> 25:05.053
[PHONE RINGS]

25:05.254 --> 25:06.722
WOMAN:
<i>Yes, Mr. Mussburger.</i>

25:06.922 --> 25:10.142
Yeah? Uh-huh. Yeah.

25:10.342 --> 25:11.969
Out! Out of the office!

25:14.680 --> 25:15.977
Down three points, huh?

25:16.181 --> 25:18.525
That's encouraging.
How about New York?

25:19.435 --> 25:21.529
Not that way, through the door!

25:21.729 --> 25:24.232
WOMAN: <i>Sir, it'll take three hours</i>
<i>to retype the Bumstead contract...</i>

25:25.107 --> 25:28.031
MUSSBURGER: Where are you going?
Get out of here! Stop that!

25:28.235 --> 25:29.953
WOMAN:
<i>Mr. Bumstead's threatening to leave.</i>

25:30.154 --> 25:31.246
Not the whole contract,
just the first page.

25:31.447 --> 25:32.414
[NORVILLE MUMBLING]

25:32.614 --> 25:34.491
I'll be there.
Give him another magazine.

25:34.700 --> 25:36.702
WOMAN: He <i>says he'll leave.</i>
MUSSBURGER: I said I'll be there!

25:36.910 --> 25:38.912
<i>And you're wife's been trying to reach you.</i>

25:39.121 --> 25:42.341
Up on your feet! We don't crawl
here at Hudsucker Industries!

25:42.541 --> 25:44.134
- My leg is on fire!
- No assumptions!

25:44.334 --> 25:48.589
It's early yet. Just let me know
where we stand at the closing bell.

25:48.797 --> 25:50.515
[PHONE RINGING]

25:53.594 --> 25:54.846
[GRUNTS]

25:57.431 --> 25:59.775
Oh, my God, the Bumstead contract!

25:59.975 --> 26:02.228
[NORVILLE MUMBLING]

26:05.314 --> 26:07.157
No magazines! No coffee!

26:07.357 --> 26:12.284
Mussburger! I wanna see Mussburger!
Or did he jump out a window too?

26:12.946 --> 26:16.576
Don't worry, Mr. Mussburger, I got you!
I got you by your pants.

26:19.578 --> 26:21.330
Pants?

26:25.000 --> 26:28.846
Mr. Mussburger, I'm gonna
give your pants a nice double stitch.

26:29.046 --> 26:33.927
It'll make them real strong
and you're gonna look real sharp.

26:34.134 --> 26:39.265
- No, single stitch is fine.
- But the double stitch, she lasts forever.

26:40.265 --> 26:43.895
Why on earth would I want
a double stitch?

26:44.103 --> 26:45.821
To pad your account.

26:46.021 --> 26:47.819
Single stitch is fine.

26:53.904 --> 26:55.451
Damn!

26:57.825 --> 27:01.125
[HUMMING]

27:01.328 --> 27:05.208
Oh, what the heck!
Mr. Mussburger is such a nice man...

27:05.415 --> 27:08.544
...I'm gonna give him
a double stitch anyway. Heh-heh-heh.

27:09.086 --> 27:12.807
Ah. That's some strong stitch, you bet!

27:23.559 --> 27:25.937
[ALL LAUGHING]

27:39.908 --> 27:41.876
[NORVILLE LAUGHING]

27:51.044 --> 27:53.012
[CONTINUES LAUGHING]

27:57.259 --> 27:59.227
[GROUP LAUGHING]

28:20.908 --> 28:22.876
[LAUGHING]

28:31.668 --> 28:33.636
[LAUGHING]

28:58.737 --> 29:01.741
AL:
"The Einstein of Enterprise."

29:01.949 --> 29:04.327
"The Edison of Industry."

29:04.701 --> 29:07.580
"The Billion-Dollar Cranium!"

29:08.830 --> 29:11.174
"Idea Man!"

29:12.209 --> 29:14.553
And not one of you has given me
a story on him!

29:14.753 --> 29:16.596
Bunch of lamebrains!

29:16.797 --> 29:19.141
Facts, figures, charts.
They never sold a newspaper!

29:19.341 --> 29:21.935
I read this morning's <i>Argus</i>,
let me tell you something.

29:22.135 --> 29:24.809
I'd wrap a fish in it!
I'd use it as kindling!

29:25.013 --> 29:27.607
I'd train my poodle on it
if he wasn't a French poodle...

29:27.808 --> 29:29.526
...and partial to pages of <i>Paris-Soir</i>.

29:29.726 --> 29:32.650
But I wouldn't shell out a hard-earned
nickel to read the thing!

29:32.854 --> 29:34.777
Come on, chief, give us a break.

29:34.982 --> 29:37.826
Sure, Tibbs. Take a break.

29:38.026 --> 29:40.575
Go to Florida. Lie in the sun.

29:40.779 --> 29:43.373
Wait for a coconut to drop.
File a story on it.

29:43.573 --> 29:46.793
It'd be more of a grabber than your piece
on the county grain surplus!

29:46.994 --> 29:49.668
The human angle!
That's what sells papers!

29:49.871 --> 29:53.171
We need a front page with a heart
and the Idea Man can put it there!

29:53.375 --> 29:55.002
Look, chief, if we had more access...

29:55.210 --> 29:57.759
If a frog had wings
it wouldn't bump it's ass a-hopping.

29:57.963 --> 29:59.761
I don't want excuses, I want results!

29:59.965 --> 30:02.514
What makes the Idea Man tick?
Where's he from?

30:02.718 --> 30:06.348
I want to know everything about him!
Has he got a girl? Has he got parents?

30:06.555 --> 30:08.603
Everybody has parents.

30:08.807 --> 30:10.855
All right, how many?

30:11.393 --> 30:14.522
How about it, Parkinson?
You've been awful quiet over there.

30:14.730 --> 30:16.858
- Uh...
- Still waters run deep.

30:17.065 --> 30:19.693
Only thing deep with Parkinson
are the holes in his ears.

30:19.901 --> 30:21.744
Yes, Idea Man.

30:21.945 --> 30:25.370
What are his hopes and dreams,
his desires and aspirations?

30:25.574 --> 30:28.202
Does he think all the time
or a certain portion of the day?

30:28.410 --> 30:30.583
How tall is he? Shoe size?
Where does he sleep?

30:30.787 --> 30:32.209
What does he have for breakfast?

30:32.414 --> 30:34.291
Does he put jam on his toast
or doesn't he?

30:34.499 --> 30:36.547
If not, why not and since when?

30:37.294 --> 30:38.716
Well?

30:39.671 --> 30:41.719
Ah. You're useless.

30:41.923 --> 30:44.722
Yes. Idea Man. "Creator."

30:44.926 --> 30:47.975
"Innovator." "Cerebrator."

30:48.180 --> 30:49.898
WOMAN: Fake!
- Huh?

30:50.098 --> 30:51.816
I tell you, the guy's a phony.

30:52.017 --> 30:53.564
AL: Phony, huh?
- As a three-dollar bill.

30:53.769 --> 30:55.191
- Says who?
- Says me, Amy Archer!

30:55.395 --> 30:57.739
Why is he an Idea Man?
Because Hudsucker says he is?

30:57.939 --> 31:00.567
What are his ideas?
Why can't anyone interview him?

31:00.776 --> 31:03.404
Five bucks says
she mentions her Pulitzer.

31:03.612 --> 31:05.580
Again? You're on.

31:05.781 --> 31:07.829
Just take a look at the mug on this guy.

31:08.033 --> 31:10.786
The jutting eyebrows, the simian forehead,
the idiotic grin.

31:10.994 --> 31:15.295
He has a face only a mother could love
on payday.

31:15.499 --> 31:18.093
The only story here is how
this guy made a monkey out of you, AI.

31:18.293 --> 31:19.260
[GIBBERS]

31:19.461 --> 31:21.008
Yeah, monkey or not,
I'm still editor of this rag.

31:21.213 --> 31:24.217
You were doing the piece on the FBI.
"Hoover: When Will He Marry?"

31:24.424 --> 31:27.428
- I filed it yesterday. Nice tie, Earl.
- Well, do a follow-up.

31:27.636 --> 31:29.559
"Hoover: Crime Buster or Pantywaist?"

31:29.763 --> 31:33.267
The rest of you mugs get off your brains
and get me that Idea Man story!

31:33.475 --> 31:36.194
AI, he's the bunk.

31:41.983 --> 31:44.452
- I'll stake my Pulitzer on it!
MAN: Hmm.

31:46.321 --> 31:48.289
Say, buddy,
where'd you get the new duds?

31:48.490 --> 31:51.790
Say, buddy, how did old bucket butt
like his blue letter? Heh.

31:51.993 --> 31:55.338
Did he bust a gut? Did he die?
Well, hello, Mr. Mussburger.

31:55.539 --> 31:58.258
- Lobby, we haven't got all day.
- Right away, Mr. Mussburger.

31:58.750 --> 32:00.593
How are you this fine morning, sir?

32:01.253 --> 32:03.722
It's been a pleasure serving you today,
sir.

32:03.922 --> 32:06.766
It's been a pleasure serving you too, uh,
buddy.

32:06.967 --> 32:09.015
Uh, Sid, shouldn't we be
a little concerned...

32:09.219 --> 32:11.972
...with the downward spiral of our stock
these past few days?

32:12.180 --> 32:14.478
You're the expert,
but at the Muncie College...

32:14.683 --> 32:16.435
Relax, it's only natural...

32:16.643 --> 32:19.988
...in a period of transition for the more
timid element to run for cover.

32:20.188 --> 32:21.656
Like I said, you're the expert...

32:21.857 --> 32:24.280
...but do you remember the plan
I outlined for you...

32:24.484 --> 32:27.328
...the day I set fire to your office?
The day I was promoted?

32:27.529 --> 32:32.786
I do remember and I was impressed.
But that's all forgotten now.

32:33.952 --> 32:35.374
NORVILLE:
Oh. Thank you, Sid.

32:35.996 --> 32:39.341
The reason I mention it is it requires
such a small capital investment...

32:39.541 --> 32:41.009
Again, you are the expert here.

32:41.209 --> 32:43.428
...but there's such an enormous
potential profit...

32:43.628 --> 32:46.632
...given the discretionary income
of the burgeoning middle-class.

32:46.840 --> 32:47.841
[TIRES SCREECH]

32:48.049 --> 32:50.143
So if you agree, I'd like to bounce the idea
off a few people at lunch.

32:50.343 --> 32:51.515
Sure, sure.

32:51.720 --> 32:55.350
Tell whoever you want.
I'd like to hear about it at some point too.

33:04.608 --> 33:09.205
- I got gas, Benny.
- Yeah. Tell me about it.

33:09.404 --> 33:12.374
LOU:
No kidding, Benny. I got gas.

33:12.574 --> 33:15.919
BENNY: You get the special?
LOU: Far from it.

33:17.787 --> 33:19.255
[LOU WHISTLES]

33:19.456 --> 33:21.174
LOU:
Enter the dame.

33:21.374 --> 33:23.843
BENNY:
There's one in every story.

33:24.044 --> 33:26.718
LOU: Ten bucks says
she's looking for a handout.

33:26.922 --> 33:30.267
BENNY: Twenty bucks says not here,
she don't find one.

33:30.467 --> 33:33.220
LOU: She's looking for her mark.
BENNY: She finds him.

33:33.428 --> 33:38.559
LOU: She sits down
and orders a light lunch.

33:39.267 --> 33:41.816
BENNY:
How will she pay for this lunch?

33:42.020 --> 33:45.445
LOU: She looks through her purse.
BENNY: No money.

33:45.649 --> 33:48.152
LOU:
The mark notices.

33:48.777 --> 33:52.077
- He's not noticing, Benny.
BENNY: Maybe he's wise.

33:52.280 --> 33:54.703
LOU:
He don't look wise.

33:55.992 --> 33:57.335
BENNY:
Plan two.

33:57.536 --> 33:59.459
Here come the waterworks.

33:59.663 --> 34:01.711
LOU: Yellowstone.
BENNY: Old Faithful.

34:01.915 --> 34:03.883
LOU:
Hello, Niagara.

34:04.084 --> 34:06.837
BENNY: He notices.
LOU: She's distressed.

34:07.045 --> 34:08.842
BENNY:
He's concerned.

34:09.047 --> 34:11.219
LOU:
She explains her predicament.

34:11.424 --> 34:16.021
LOU AND BENNY [IN UNISON]:
And enter the light lunch.

34:16.221 --> 34:20.601
BENNY: She's got other problems.
LOU: There's illness in the family.

34:20.809 --> 34:23.608
BENNY: Her mother needs an operation.
LOU: Urgently.

34:23.812 --> 34:26.565
BENNY: Adenoids.
LOU: No, Benny.

34:27.023 --> 34:29.150
Lumbago.

34:29.359 --> 34:31.532
BENNY:
That gag's got whiskers on it.

34:31.735 --> 34:34.409
LOU:
Uh-oh. He ain't biting, Benny.

34:34.614 --> 34:37.618
BENNY: She's losing him, Lou.
LOU: Maybe he's wise.

34:37.826 --> 34:39.954
BENNY:
He don't look wise.

34:40.161 --> 34:42.789
LOU: How does she pull this out?
BENNY: He's getting away.

34:42.998 --> 34:46.422
LOU: She better think fast.
BENNY: She isn't.

34:46.626 --> 34:48.754
LOU AND BENNY [IN UNISON]:
She is!

34:48.962 --> 34:50.804
LOU:
She's good, Benny.

34:51.005 --> 34:53.134
BENNY:
She's damn good, Lou.

34:53.842 --> 34:56.094
Can I get you boys anything else?

34:58.179 --> 34:59.772
Bromo.

35:00.181 --> 35:01.774
Bromo.

35:03.476 --> 35:06.980
AMY: I'm sorry we had to take the stairs.
It was just that horrible elevator boy.

35:07.188 --> 35:10.112
I can't say how much I appreciate
your listening to my story.

35:10.317 --> 35:14.322
I'm lucky to find someone in this bustling
city with a stout heart and a ready ear.

35:14.529 --> 35:17.453
At any rate, there I was traveling
this great country.

35:17.657 --> 35:18.783
Some I met were kind to me,
others exceedingly cruel.

35:18.992 --> 35:20.039
[NORVILLE PANTING]

35:20.243 --> 35:22.462
Traveling by motor bus, rail,
even by thumb.

35:22.662 --> 35:23.959
The couch, please.

35:24.164 --> 35:27.589
Hoarding every dollar, counting
every nickel, pinching every penny.

35:27.792 --> 35:30.511
It's been a long road leading
to the coffee shop downstairs.

35:30.712 --> 35:34.091
Not that I'd trade a day, an hour,
a moment of it for anything.

35:34.299 --> 35:35.721
I don't know what came over me.

35:35.925 --> 35:37.848
It was the shock of eating
after so long...

35:38.053 --> 35:40.932
...without the enzymes kicking in
after so long...

35:41.139 --> 35:44.769
[MUTED DIALOGUE]

35:45.143 --> 35:48.192
Then you couldn't possibly know
what it is to be tired and hungry.

35:48.396 --> 35:50.319
- Hungry, anyway.
- I don't wanna bore you...

35:50.523 --> 35:52.742
...with all details of my life.
Not a happy story.

35:52.942 --> 35:55.240
I'm jobless
but not for want of trying.

35:55.445 --> 35:58.915
I'm friendless, with no one to take care
of me and had you not come along...

35:59.115 --> 36:01.334
- ...exactly when you did...
NORVILLE: I, myself...

36:01.534 --> 36:03.787
At any rate, I arrived in town
not 10 days ago...

36:03.995 --> 36:07.340
...full of dreams and aspirations,
anxious to make my way in the world...

36:07.540 --> 36:08.792
...a little naive perhaps...

36:09.000 --> 36:11.048
...but armed with determination,
work ethic...

36:11.252 --> 36:12.720
...and a belief in the future...

36:12.921 --> 36:14.889
- I, myself...
AMY:...only to have that belief...

36:15.090 --> 36:18.344
...that unsullied optimism, dashed against
the marble of the workplace.

36:18.551 --> 36:21.555
Such is life. Seek and you shall
find. Work and you shall prosper.

36:21.763 --> 36:23.231
- Cigarette?
- No, thank you.

36:23.431 --> 36:25.809
Seek and you shall find,
work and you shall prosper.

36:26.017 --> 36:28.236
These were the watchwords
of my education...

36:28.436 --> 36:30.188
...the values instilled in me...

36:30.397 --> 36:33.526
...while I was growing up in a little town
you've never heard of.

36:33.733 --> 36:35.235
- Mind if I join you?
- Be my guest.

36:35.443 --> 36:37.537
A little town you've probably
never heard of...

36:37.737 --> 36:39.535
...a dusty crossroads of which
you've probably never heard.

36:39.739 --> 36:40.740
[SCREAMS]

36:41.950 --> 36:45.124
Excuse me. Executive washroom.

36:45.829 --> 36:47.456
[NORVILLE GROANING]

36:47.664 --> 36:49.416
Are you all right?

36:49.624 --> 36:51.092
[NORVILLE YELLING]

36:51.292 --> 36:54.466
Is it your lunch?
The chicken Ã  la king?

36:56.589 --> 37:01.641
- Is the Ã  la king repeating on you?
- No, I'm fine. You were saying?

37:03.346 --> 37:04.472
Uh...

37:04.681 --> 37:06.934
[IN LOW VOICE]
Values, watchwords, tender years.

37:07.142 --> 37:10.772
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
A town you've probably never heard of.

37:10.979 --> 37:13.448
Muncie, Indiana.

37:13.648 --> 37:18.870
- You're from Muncie?
- Why, yes. Do you know it?

37:20.530 --> 37:24.285
Uh... Uhn!

37:24.659 --> 37:26.661
[NORVILLE YELLING AND GRUNTING]

37:36.087 --> 37:37.805
[SINGING]
<i>Fight on</i>

37:38.006 --> 37:41.306
<i>Fight on</i>
<i>Dear old Muncie</i>

37:41.509 --> 37:42.806
<i>Fight on</i>

37:43.011 --> 37:45.480
<i>Hoist the gold and blue</i>

37:45.680 --> 37:49.480
<i>You'll be tattered</i>
<i>Torn and hurting</i>

37:49.684 --> 37:54.315
<i>Once the Muncie's done with</i>

37:54.522 --> 37:57.776
<i>You</i>

37:57.984 --> 38:00.908
<i>You</i>

38:01.112 --> 38:06.585
- Go, Eagles!
- Go, Eagles!

38:06.785 --> 38:09.208
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

38:10.747 --> 38:11.794
A Muncie girl!

38:11.956 --> 38:13.754
- What do you know about that?
- Hmm.

38:14.876 --> 38:15.923
I'll tell you what, Amy.

38:16.127 --> 38:18.221
I'm gonna cancel the rest
of my appointments...

38:18.421 --> 38:19.968
...and get you a job here at Hud.

38:20.173 --> 38:21.846
Oh, no! Really...

38:22.050 --> 38:25.395
Don't bother to thank me. It's easy.
I know where a vacancy just came up.

38:25.595 --> 38:27.848
- Mailroom. This will only take a moment.
MAN [OVER INTERCOM]: <i>Yeah.</i>

38:28.056 --> 38:29.854
Good afternoon, this is Norville Barnes.

38:30.058 --> 38:31.685
MUSSBURGER [OVER INTERCOM]:
<i>Barnes! Where the hell have you been?</i>

38:31.893 --> 38:34.988
<i>- Where's my voucher?</i>
- Um...

38:35.188 --> 38:36.861
- I'm not sure.
<i>- I need that voucher!</i>

38:37.065 --> 38:39.193
<i>I told you a week ago it was important!</i>

38:40.068 --> 38:42.070
Ahem, I'm president of the company now.

38:42.278 --> 38:45.657
<i>I don't care</i>
<i>if you're president of the company!</i>

38:45.865 --> 38:47.867
<i>I need the voucher now!</i>

38:49.327 --> 38:51.546
Look, why don't you work in here
with me?

38:51.746 --> 38:53.919
Are you familiar
with the mimeograph machine?

38:54.082 --> 38:59.009
Well, of course. I went to the
Muncie Secretarial, uh, Polytechnic.

38:59.212 --> 39:01.055
A Muncie girl! Can you beat that?

39:01.965 --> 39:04.559
I just don't know
how to thank you, Mr. Barnes.

39:04.759 --> 39:06.557
Please, Norville.

39:06.761 --> 39:10.641
NORVILLE: Go, Eagles! Heh.
AMY: Go, Eagles!

39:10.849 --> 39:13.147
[SMITTY LAUGHING]

39:13.768 --> 39:16.942
"Once the Munce..." Holy moly!

39:17.146 --> 39:20.400
Is this guy from Chumpsville?
I even pulled the old mother routine.

39:20.608 --> 39:21.780
- Adenoids?
- Lumbago.

39:22.277 --> 39:24.120
Phew. That gag's got whiskers on it.

39:24.320 --> 39:25.412
AMY: I tell you,
the Hudsucker board's up to something.

39:25.613 --> 39:26.705
[PHONE RINGING]

39:26.906 --> 39:29.785
What's a six-letter word
for an affliction of the hypothalamus?

39:29.993 --> 39:32.462
And it's a cinch... Goiter.
...This guy isn't in on it.

39:32.662 --> 39:35.290
SMITTY: She's right here.
- How much time to make the late final?

39:35.498 --> 39:37.796
- Chief.
- Tsk. Hiya, chief.

39:38.001 --> 39:39.878
Just the person I wanted to apologize to.

39:40.086 --> 39:43.761
- About seven minutes.
- Yeah, I was all wet about your Idea Man.

39:43.965 --> 39:48.721
Well, thanks for being so generous.
It is human and you are divine.

39:48.928 --> 39:51.272
No, he's no faker.

39:51.472 --> 39:54.772
He's 100 percent real McCoy,
beware of imitations, genuine article.

39:54.976 --> 39:58.355
The guy's a real moron,
as in a five-letter word for imbecile.

39:58.563 --> 40:01.692
Oh, as pure a specimen
as I've ever run across. Okay.

40:01.900 --> 40:04.278
If working at the <i>Argus</i>
doesn't make me an expert...

40:04.485 --> 40:07.989
...then my name isn't Amy Archer
and I never won the Pulitzer Prize.

40:08.197 --> 40:09.824
In 1957.

40:10.033 --> 40:13.287
My, oh, my series
on the reunited triplets.

40:13.494 --> 40:16.748
Well, come down here, hammerhead,
and I'll show it to you!

40:16.956 --> 40:19.300
What's a three-letter word
for a flightless bird?

40:19.500 --> 40:20.501
AMY:
Not now, I'm busy.

40:20.710 --> 40:23.680
Right, I said, "hammerhead,"
as in a 10-letter word for a smug...

40:23.880 --> 40:25.052
...bullying newspaper man.

40:25.256 --> 40:27.054
Gnu. Who couldn't find... That's G-N-U.

40:27.258 --> 40:30.603
Couldn't find the Empire State Building
with a compass, map and a guide.

40:30.803 --> 40:33.773
Or is it Emu? That's just potatoes.
Here comes the gravy.

40:33.973 --> 40:35.270
The chump really likes me.

40:35.475 --> 40:38.354
- Ah. A Muncie girl!
- Better off falling for a rattlesnake.

40:38.561 --> 40:41.110
This guy's just a patsy
and I'm gonna find out what for.

40:41.314 --> 40:43.316
There's a real story here,
some kind of plot.

40:43.524 --> 40:45.492
A set-up.
Oh, and say, did I tell you?

40:45.693 --> 40:47.411
- He didn't offer you money?
- A sawbuck!

40:47.612 --> 40:49.580
Ten smackers! Let's grab a highball!

40:49.781 --> 40:51.454
- On Norville Barnes.
- Yeah.

40:51.658 --> 40:52.659
[AMY WHISTLES]

40:52.867 --> 40:54.414
Copy!

41:23.064 --> 41:25.158
Ms. Smith, would you come in
and take a letter?

41:26.526 --> 41:28.574
Of all the cockamamy...

41:30.446 --> 41:33.199
Did you see the front page
of today's <i>Manhattan Argus</i> ?

41:33.408 --> 41:37.584
Well, I, uh, didn't bother to read the article.
I didn't think the picture did you justice.

41:38.287 --> 41:39.755
Well, the picture's fine.

41:39.956 --> 41:42.254
It's what that knuckle-headed
dame wrote underneath.

41:42.458 --> 41:44.927
Of all the irresponsible...
Take this down.

41:45.128 --> 41:47.222
Dear, Ms. Archer.

41:47.422 --> 41:50.972
I call you "Miss" because you seem
to have missed the boat completely.

41:51.175 --> 41:53.143
How would you know if I'm an imbecile?

41:53.344 --> 41:55.938
You didn't have the guts to come
interview me man-to-man!

41:56.139 --> 41:57.857
Change "man-to-man"
to "face-to-face."

41:58.057 --> 42:01.231
Change "face-to-face" to "eye-to-eye"
and "guts" to "common decency."

42:01.436 --> 42:03.564
These wild speculations
about my intelligence...

42:03.771 --> 42:06.069
...these preposterous inventions
would be suited...

42:06.274 --> 42:09.027
...to the pages of
<i>Amazing Tales Magazine</i>.

42:09.235 --> 42:11.488
If the editors of the <i>Manhattan Argus</i>
see fit...

42:11.696 --> 42:13.915
...to publish the rantings
of a disordered mind...

42:14.115 --> 42:16.493
...perhaps they will see fit
to publish this letter.

42:16.701 --> 42:18.123
But I most seriously doubt it.

42:18.327 --> 42:21.297
As I doubt also that you could find a home
at <i>Amazing Tales</i>...

42:21.497 --> 42:24.091
...a periodical which I have enjoyed
for many years.

42:24.292 --> 42:27.136
Sincerely, et cetera, et cetera,
et cetera.

42:33.801 --> 42:35.769
Is that all, Mr. Barnes?

42:35.970 --> 42:37.313
Uh...

42:37.889 --> 42:41.393
You know me, Amy, better than this dame.
Do you think I'm an imbecile?

42:41.809 --> 42:43.436
Oh, well, I'm sure I...

42:43.644 --> 42:46.864
Tell the truth. I trust you.
I place a lot of stock in your opinion.

42:48.316 --> 42:50.865
- Well...
- Oh, sure, heh, you're biased.

42:51.069 --> 42:52.116
You're a fellow Muncian, heh.

42:52.320 --> 42:53.321
Hmm.

42:53.529 --> 42:58.285
But let me ask you a question:
Would an imbecile come up with this?

43:04.040 --> 43:06.008
I designed it myself.

43:06.793 --> 43:10.343
This sweet baby will put
Hudsucker right back on top.

43:10.546 --> 43:11.889
Uh-huh.

43:12.632 --> 43:14.305
You know, for kids.

43:17.303 --> 43:19.601
Why don't I just type this up?

43:19.806 --> 43:22.650
Oh, no, Amy, that won't be necessary.
I shouldn't send it.

43:22.850 --> 43:25.148
She's just doing her job, I guess.

43:25.353 --> 43:27.856
I don't know, maybe she does deserve it.

43:28.064 --> 43:31.113
Maybe she should have come in here
and faced you man-to-man.

43:31.317 --> 43:32.318
NORVILLE:
She had a deadline.

43:32.527 --> 43:36.532
Sure, but she still could've gotten
your side, for the record.

43:36.739 --> 43:39.538
Well, it's done now. What's the use
of grousing about it? Ha, ha.

43:39.742 --> 43:42.962
Forget the letter, Amy,
I just had to blow off some steam. Heh.

43:43.162 --> 43:45.881
She's probably just a little confused.

43:46.415 --> 43:49.840
- Confused?
- She's probably a fast-talking career gal...

43:50.044 --> 43:52.763
...thinks she's one of the boys.
If you know what I mean, heh.

43:52.964 --> 43:55.513
Oh, I'm quite sure
I don't know what you mean.

43:55.716 --> 43:58.185
Suffers from one of these complexes
they have nowadays.

43:58.386 --> 43:59.683
Seems pretty obvious.

43:59.887 --> 44:02.481
She's probably very unattractive
and bitter about it.

44:02.682 --> 44:04.355
- Oh, is that it?
- Yeah.

44:04.559 --> 44:06.436
She probably dresses in men's clothing...

44:06.644 --> 44:08.738
...drinks with the guys
at the watering hole...

44:08.938 --> 44:11.407
...hobnobs with some smooth-talking
heel named Biff...

44:11.607 --> 44:13.359
- ...or Smoocher or, uh...
- Smitty.

44:13.568 --> 44:15.912
Exactly. I bet she's ugly, real ugly.

44:16.112 --> 44:18.615
Otherwise, why isn't her picture
next to her byline?

44:18.823 --> 44:22.123
Oh, maybe she puts her work
ahead of her personal appearance.

44:22.326 --> 44:24.420
I bet that's exactly what she tells herself.

44:24.620 --> 44:27.169
But you and I both know
she's a dried-up, bitter old maid.

44:27.373 --> 44:28.374
[CHUCKLES]

44:28.583 --> 44:30.756
Amy, how about we grab
a little dinner and a show after work?

44:30.960 --> 44:32.507
I was thinking maybe <i>The King and I</i>.

44:33.963 --> 44:35.340
Uh, how about <i>Oklahoma</i>!?

44:35.548 --> 44:38.051
Norville, you don't know
a thing about that woman!

44:38.259 --> 44:39.761
You don't know who she really is.

44:39.969 --> 44:42.313
And only a numbskull thinks
he knows things...

44:42.513 --> 44:44.641
...about things he
knows nothing, uh, about.

44:46.642 --> 44:48.895
NORVILLE:
Say, what gives?

45:02.909 --> 45:05.708
[WHISTLING]

45:12.585 --> 45:14.804
[DOOR OPENS]

45:40.947 --> 45:42.039
Uh-huh.

45:42.698 --> 45:44.496
[CLOSES BOOK]

46:50.474 --> 46:53.819
[TALKING INDISTINCTLY]

46:55.354 --> 46:56.731
The inventory of the Jacksonville...

46:56.939 --> 47:00.239
...facility should be reduced
by 15 percent.

47:00.443 --> 47:02.411
Memo from the desk
of Sidney J. Mussburger...

47:02.611 --> 47:05.160
MAN: What are you doing down there,
Ms. Archer?

47:05.364 --> 47:06.991
Huh?

47:14.081 --> 47:17.301
Who are you?
How did you know who I am?

47:17.501 --> 47:19.253
[CHUCKLES]

47:19.462 --> 47:23.217
I suspect Old Moses knows
just about everything...

47:23.424 --> 47:26.223
...leastways if it concerns Hudsucker.

47:26.427 --> 47:28.555
But who are you?
What do you do here?

47:28.763 --> 47:33.894
I keep the old circle turning.
This old clock needs plenty of care.

47:34.101 --> 47:36.354
Time is money, Ms. Archer.

47:36.562 --> 47:39.190
And money drives
that old global economy...

47:39.398 --> 47:41.742
...and keeps Big Daddy Earth
spinning around.

47:41.942 --> 47:45.116
- See, without that capital formation...
- Yeah, yeah.

47:45.321 --> 47:48.746
Say, you won't tell anyone about me,
will you?

47:48.949 --> 47:53.955
I don't tell no one nothing
unless they ask.

47:54.163 --> 47:56.586
That just ain't Old Moses' way.

47:56.791 --> 47:58.759
So if you know
everything about Hudsucker...

47:58.959 --> 48:02.088
...tell me why the board decided
to make Norville Barnes president?

48:02.463 --> 48:05.558
Well, that even surprised Old Moses
at first.

48:05.758 --> 48:08.807
- I didn't think the board was that smart.
- "That smart"?

48:09.011 --> 48:10.934
But then I figured it out.

48:11.138 --> 48:14.187
They did it because they figured
young Norville for an imbecile...

48:14.392 --> 48:15.939
...like some other people I know.

48:16.435 --> 48:19.689
Now, why on earth would the board
want a nitwit to be president?

48:19.897 --> 48:24.118
Because they're little piglets.
They're trying to inspire panic...

48:24.318 --> 48:27.697
...make that stock cheap so they can
snatch it all up for themselves.

48:27.905 --> 48:32.081
But Norville, he's got some tricks up
his sleeve. He does.

48:32.284 --> 48:34.161
You know, for kids.

48:34.370 --> 48:35.462
- Hee-hee.
- Uh-huh.

48:35.663 --> 48:39.008
Yeah, he's a smart one, that Norville.

48:39.208 --> 48:42.633
But I guess you don't really know him
any better than that board does...

48:42.837 --> 48:43.804
...do you, Ms. Archer?

48:44.797 --> 48:47.641
- Well, maybe I...
- And only some kind of knuckle-head...

48:47.842 --> 48:50.641
...thinks she knows things
about things she, uh...

48:51.762 --> 48:54.390
When she don't, uh...

48:54.598 --> 48:57.943
- How'd that go?
- Well, it's hardly the same.

48:58.144 --> 49:00.613
Why, you don't even know
your own self.

49:00.813 --> 49:04.488
You ain't exactly the genuine article,
are you, Ms. Archer?

49:04.692 --> 49:06.820
Yes, well, in connection with my job...

49:07.027 --> 49:09.530
...sometimes I have to, uh, go undercover,
as it were.

49:09.738 --> 49:11.490
I don't mean that.

49:11.699 --> 49:15.670
Why are you pretending to be
such a hard old sourpuss?

49:15.870 --> 49:18.168
Ain't gonna
never make you happy.

49:20.082 --> 49:22.505
I'm happy enough.

49:22.710 --> 49:24.178
[LAUGHING]

49:24.753 --> 49:26.175
Okay, Ms. Archer.

49:27.715 --> 49:29.308
I got gears to see to.

49:29.508 --> 49:31.476
[LAUGHING]

49:34.472 --> 49:36.816
I'm plenty happy!

49:43.230 --> 49:44.698
AMY:
Hello?

49:46.901 --> 49:48.949
- I can't print that!
- Why not? It's all true.

49:49.153 --> 49:51.872
The board's using him to depress
the stock to buy it cheap.

49:52.072 --> 49:53.995
It's pure speculation!
They'd have my butt in a satchel!

49:54.200 --> 49:57.579
- Ah. Old satchel butt.
AMY: I know they're gonna buy that stock.

49:57.786 --> 49:59.254
You don't.
They haven't bought it.

49:59.455 --> 50:01.628
The stock's cheap!
What are they waiting for?

50:01.832 --> 50:04.301
- I don't know.
- Amy's hunches are usually pretty good.

50:04.502 --> 50:07.176
You don't accuse somebody of stock
manipulation on a hunch.

50:07.379 --> 50:09.677
The readers aren't interested
in sensationalism...

50:09.882 --> 50:12.726
...gossip, unsupported speculation!
Facts! Figures! Charts!

50:12.927 --> 50:14.895
Those are the tools
of the newspaper trade.

50:15.095 --> 50:18.190
It's as if you're trying to take the heat off
this Barnes numbskull.

50:18.390 --> 50:20.518
Oh, come on, chief. That's a low blow.

50:20.726 --> 50:23.354
Archer's not going to go gooey
for a corn-fed idiot.

50:23.562 --> 50:26.862
I was out of line. But you're out of line
with this stock-swindle story.

50:27.066 --> 50:29.285
Give me more of that
"moron from Sheboygan" stuff.

50:29.485 --> 50:30.862
- Muncie.
- Whatever.

50:31.070 --> 50:32.413
That's what sells newspapers!

50:32.613 --> 50:35.162
I've got a harder story,
"The Sap From The City Desk!"

50:35.366 --> 50:37.835
- Watch it!
- It's about a dim-witted editor who...

50:38.035 --> 50:40.037
Easy, tough guy. Heh-heh-heh.

50:42.748 --> 50:44.625
Does this suit look mannish to you?

50:44.833 --> 50:47.131
SMITTY:
Yeah, sure. Let's grab a highball.

50:47.962 --> 50:49.179
AMY:
Back off!

50:49.380 --> 50:51.098
Smoocher!

50:52.341 --> 50:55.345
Eh. What gives?

51:05.729 --> 51:07.697
[CHATTERING]

51:10.484 --> 51:13.909
A man of great managerial potency.

51:14.113 --> 51:16.457
My husband is also a president.

51:16.657 --> 51:19.957
Sears Braithwaite of Bullard.
Do you know him?

51:20.160 --> 51:22.504
Your companion is an ode!

51:22.705 --> 51:25.128
A lyric! Are you betrothed?

51:25.332 --> 51:27.710
Amy works in my office.
She runs, uh...

51:27.918 --> 51:32.264
- Oh, the folly of youth.
- Those green remembered hills.

51:32.464 --> 51:35.889
That bourn
from which no traveler returns.

51:36.093 --> 51:38.221
I once ran the mimeograph
for Sidney.

51:38.429 --> 51:41.729
Though engaged at the time
to <i>quelqu'un d'autre</i>...

51:41.932 --> 51:45.653
...my water-cooler romance
became a mad passion.

51:45.853 --> 51:48.857
Uh. An <i>amour fou</i>.
A <i>folie Ã  deux</i>.

51:49.064 --> 51:50.782
[LAUGHS]

51:50.983 --> 51:53.657
I'm brushing up on my French
with the most charming man...

51:53.861 --> 51:55.363
- ...Pierre of 5th Avenue.
- Oh!

51:55.571 --> 51:57.164
- Do you know him?
- Do you know him?

51:57.364 --> 52:02.336
Sidney and I are planning a trip
to Paris and points continental.

52:02.536 --> 52:03.879
[WOMEN LAUGHING]

52:05.497 --> 52:06.498
- Oh.
- Aren't we, dear?

52:07.541 --> 52:12.672
For sure. I would like to borrow Norville
for a while, if you don't mind, dear.

52:12.880 --> 52:15.633
Oh, well, uh, frankly, I...

52:15.841 --> 52:17.684
You have a very charming wife,
Mr... Sid.

52:17.885 --> 52:19.512
So they tell me.

52:19.720 --> 52:23.224
Norville, let me shepherd you
through some of the introductions here.

52:23.432 --> 52:25.526
Try not to talk too much.

52:25.726 --> 52:28.195
Some of our biggest stockholders are...

52:28.395 --> 52:30.147
Scratch that. Say whatever you like.

52:30.356 --> 52:32.654
Shake hands here
with Sears Braithwaite of Bullard.

52:32.858 --> 52:35.156
- Sir.
- Glad to know you, Barnes.

52:35.361 --> 52:37.034
MUSSBURGER:
And this is Zebulon Cardozo...

52:37.237 --> 52:40.241
...one of Hudsucker's largest
and most loyal stockholders.

52:40.449 --> 52:42.543
What's this I hear
about you being an imbecile?

52:42.743 --> 52:44.541
What's ailing you, boy?

52:44.745 --> 52:47.749
Last week, my stock
was worth twice what it is now.

52:47.956 --> 52:50.675
I'm getting out of the whole
kit and caboodle of it, boy...

52:50.876 --> 52:53.254
...unless I see a
vast improvement.

52:53.462 --> 52:56.215
What you've got here, son,
is a range war!

52:56.423 --> 53:00.178
You're gonna have to circle our wagons
or I'm gonna get out of your wagon train.

53:00.386 --> 53:01.558
[CHUCKLES]

53:01.762 --> 53:02.888
No need for concern, sir.

53:03.097 --> 53:05.191
It's only natural in a period
of transition...

53:05.391 --> 53:07.189
...for the more timid elements
to run.

53:07.393 --> 53:10.192
Yellow? I'll show you yellow, boy!

53:10.396 --> 53:13.900
Zebulon, you mind now and quit acting
like such an old grizzly.

53:14.108 --> 53:16.577
MUSSBURGER:
Step lively here, Norville.

53:16.777 --> 53:19.747
I'm sorry, Sid, uh, I thought maybe
if I showed him the long view...

53:19.947 --> 53:22.826
And this is Thorstenson Finlandson...

53:23.033 --> 53:25.957
...who heads a radical splinter group
of disgruntled investors.

53:26.161 --> 53:27.834
Ah. Pleased to meet you,
Mr. Finlandson.

53:28.038 --> 53:30.712
It might interest you to know I studied
Finnish in high school.

53:30.916 --> 53:32.884
Let see,
I hope I'm not too rusty. Um...

53:34.086 --> 53:36.555
[SPEAKS IN FINNISH]

53:36.755 --> 53:38.223
[WOMAN SCREAMS]

53:40.884 --> 53:41.931
Ladies and gentlemen...

53:42.136 --> 53:44.355
...distinguished members
of the Hudsucker board...

53:44.555 --> 53:48.605
...I give you the Rajah of Romance,
the Ministereo of Moonlight...

53:48.809 --> 53:51.107
...the incredible,
the unforgettable...

53:51.311 --> 53:55.191
...Mr. Vic Tenetta!

53:55.482 --> 53:57.826
[CROWD APPLAUDING]

53:58.110 --> 54:00.579
[CHORUS HUMMING]

54:00.863 --> 54:04.117
Rajah, I like that.

54:04.324 --> 54:09.080
[SINGING]
<i>Take one fresh and tender kiss</i>

54:09.288 --> 54:11.131
[GASPS]

54:11.331 --> 54:17.304
<i>Add one stolen night of bliss</i>

54:18.922 --> 54:25.521
<i>One girl one boy</i>
<i>Some grief some joy</i>

54:25.721 --> 54:31.023
<i>Memories are made of this</i>

54:32.853 --> 54:34.480
<i>Don't</i>

54:40.527 --> 54:41.494
Norville?

54:45.657 --> 54:47.250
What happened?

54:47.451 --> 54:53.299
Oh, nothing. Just the more timid investors
are no longer running for cover.

54:53.499 --> 54:56.252
- Let me look.
- Sid found me the ice pack.

54:56.460 --> 54:58.963
Well, let me hold it
or you'll have a real shiner.

54:59.171 --> 55:00.388
Oh, thanks.

55:00.589 --> 55:03.684
I guess people are pretty hot
over this imbecile story.

55:03.884 --> 55:05.477
I'm sorry.

55:05.677 --> 55:06.974
Oh, it's not your fault, Amy.

55:07.179 --> 55:09.602
You're the one person
standing by me through this.

55:09.807 --> 55:13.437
Norville, there's something
I have to tell you.

55:13.644 --> 55:17.774
You see, I'm not really a secretary.

55:18.440 --> 55:20.738
- I know that, Amy.
- You do?

55:20.943 --> 55:24.038
I understand you're not very skilled yet
in the secretarial arts...

55:24.238 --> 55:27.208
...but I'll tell you a secret,
I'm not that skilled as president.

55:27.407 --> 55:31.628
- I know I put up a big front, but, uh...
- I believe in you, Norville.

55:32.454 --> 55:36.550
At least, I believe in your intentions.

55:36.750 --> 55:40.596
Oh, I don't blame them, really.
I suppose I have made a mess of things.

55:40.796 --> 55:42.890
Those folks have to protect
their investment.

55:43.090 --> 55:44.717
Most of them are very nice people.

55:44.925 --> 55:48.179
Listen, Norville, you can't trust people here
like you did in Muncie.

55:48.387 --> 55:50.230
Certain people are...

55:50.430 --> 55:54.230
See, did you ever go to the top of Larson's
feed tower and look out over the town?

55:54.434 --> 55:56.903
- What?
- On Farm Route 17?

55:57.104 --> 55:59.653
Oh, yes, in Muncie.

56:00.774 --> 56:06.452
- No, Vidalia. Farm Route 17.
- Oh, yes, 17, yes.

56:06.655 --> 56:08.874
I... Well, no, no. I never really.

56:09.074 --> 56:10.246
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

56:10.450 --> 56:14.296
The guys from the Varsity Squad
would bring their dates up there to...

56:15.289 --> 56:17.007
...hold hands.

56:17.207 --> 56:20.757
Of course, I never made Varsity.

56:22.462 --> 56:24.760
There's a place I go now.

56:24.965 --> 56:27.889
Cutest little place near my apartment
in Greenwich Village.

56:28.093 --> 56:31.643
It's called Ann's 440. It's a beatnik bar.

56:31.847 --> 56:33.440
- You don't say?
- Yes.

56:33.640 --> 56:35.608
- A beatnik bar.
- You can get carrot juice...

56:35.809 --> 56:40.781
...or Italian coffee and the people there,
well, none of them quite fit in.

56:40.981 --> 56:41.948
You'd love it.

56:42.649 --> 56:44.196
Why don't you come there with me?

56:44.401 --> 56:47.780
There's a marathon poetry-reading
on New Year's Eve. I go every year.

56:47.988 --> 56:50.116
- It's marvelous.
- Every year?

56:51.992 --> 56:56.623
Well, this year, if it's good,
I plan to make it a tradition, heh.

56:56.830 --> 56:58.503
I, uh, heh...

56:58.707 --> 57:05.591
My, it certainly is beautiful.
The people look like ants.

57:06.089 --> 57:09.639
Well, the Hindus say,
and the beatniks also...

57:09.843 --> 57:12.972
...that in our next lives some of us
will come back as ants.

57:13.180 --> 57:15.774
Some will be butterflies,
others will be elephants...

57:15.974 --> 57:17.271
...or creatures of the sea.

57:17.476 --> 57:18.853
What a beautiful thought.

57:19.061 --> 57:22.656
Hey, what do you think you were
in a previous life, Amy?

57:22.856 --> 57:27.077
Oh, I don't know. Maybe I was just, uh...

57:27.277 --> 57:31.157
...a fast-talking career gal
who thought she was one of the boys.

57:31.365 --> 57:32.787
Oh, no, Amy.

57:32.991 --> 57:35.710
Pardon me for saying so,
but I find that very far-fetched.

57:35.911 --> 57:38.505
- No, I have to tell you...
- That person would come back...

57:38.705 --> 57:40.082
...as a wildebeest or a warthog.

57:40.290 --> 57:45.888
No, I find it more likely
that you were a gazelle...

57:46.088 --> 57:50.389
...with long, graceful legs,
gamboling through the underbrush.

57:50.592 --> 57:52.720
Perhaps we met once.

57:52.928 --> 57:56.603
A chance encounter in a forest glade.

57:57.557 --> 58:01.152
I must have been an antelope
or an ibex.

58:01.353 --> 58:05.483
The times we must've had foraging
together for sustenance...

58:05.691 --> 58:08.865
...snorfling water
from a mountain stream...

58:09.069 --> 58:13.666
...picking the grubs and burrs
from one another's coats.

58:15.242 --> 58:21.045
Or perhaps we simply touched horns
briefly and went our separate ways.

58:21.248 --> 58:25.003
Oh, I wish it were that simple,
Norville.

58:25.210 --> 58:30.091
I wish I was still a gazelle
and you were an antelope...

58:30.298 --> 58:32.676
...or an ibex.

58:34.052 --> 58:35.804
Well...

58:36.638 --> 58:39.232
...can I at least call you "deer?"

58:39.433 --> 58:42.403
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

58:42.602 --> 58:43.649
You're funny.

58:43.854 --> 58:47.108
Seriously, Amy, it's what
your beatnik friends call "karma."

58:47.315 --> 58:50.535
- Karma.
- The great circle of life, death and rebirth.

58:50.736 --> 58:55.242
Yes, I think I heard of that.
What goes around, comes around.

58:55.449 --> 58:59.249
That's it. A great wheel
that gives us all what we deserve.

58:59.995 --> 59:03.090
I gotta show Sid
and all the guys I deserve their confidence.

59:03.290 --> 59:05.713
Tomorrow's my big presentation
to the board.

59:05.917 --> 59:07.669
[MOANS]

59:08.253 --> 59:11.757
Kiss me, Amy! Kiss me once for luck.

59:12.883 --> 59:16.558
Sure, Norville, sure.

59:50.378 --> 59:52.176
Shh.

59:55.634 --> 59:57.227
NORVILLE:
You know, for kids!

59:57.427 --> 59:59.646
It has economy, simplicity,
low production cost...

59:59.846 --> 01:00:01.143
...potential for mass appeal.

01:00:01.348 --> 01:00:03.316
All that spells out great profitability.

01:00:03.517 --> 01:00:06.316
I had the boys down at R&D
throw together this prototype...

01:00:06.520 --> 01:00:08.522
...so our discussion
could have some focus...

01:00:08.730 --> 01:00:12.200
...and to give you gentleman a firsthand
look at how exciting this gizmo is.

01:00:12.400 --> 01:00:15.654
It's fun, healthy, good exercise,
and the kids will just love it.

01:00:15.862 --> 01:00:18.832
We put a little sand inside
to make the experience more pleasant.

01:00:19.032 --> 01:00:22.332
But the great part is
we don't have to charge an arm and a leg.

01:00:25.038 --> 01:00:26.756
What if you tire before it's done?

01:00:26.957 --> 01:00:27.958
Does it have rules?

01:00:28.166 --> 01:00:30.134
MAN 1: Can more than one play?
MAN 2: It's a game?

01:00:30.335 --> 01:00:31.632
MAN 3: Is it a game?
ADDISON: Will it break?

01:00:31.837 --> 01:00:34.181
MAN 4: It better break eventually.
MAN 5: Is there an object?

01:00:34.381 --> 01:00:37.009
MAN 6: What if you tire before it's done?
MAN 7: Does it have batteries?

01:00:37.217 --> 01:00:39.470
MAN 8: Could we charge extra for them?
ADDISON: Is it safe for toddlers?

01:00:39.845 --> 01:00:41.313
MAN 2:
How do you know you're finished?

01:00:41.513 --> 01:00:42.514
MAN 5:
How does it stop?

01:00:42.722 --> 01:00:44.975
MAN 8: Is that a boy's model?
MAN 9: Can a parent assemble it?

01:00:45.183 --> 01:00:49.029
MAN 4: What if you tire before it's done?
MAN 7: Is there a larger model for the obese?

01:00:49.229 --> 01:00:51.448
What the hell is it?

01:00:51.648 --> 01:00:55.243
Well, it's a... It's a...

01:00:55.443 --> 01:00:56.444
It's a...

01:00:56.653 --> 01:00:57.700
MUSSBURGER:
Brilliant!

01:00:59.614 --> 01:01:01.207
Genius.

01:01:01.867 --> 01:01:05.371
It's exactly what Hudsucker Industry
needs at this juncture.

01:01:05.579 --> 01:01:06.705
Sure, sure.

01:01:06.913 --> 01:01:11.919
Even a blind man can tell you there'll be
an enormous demand for this, uh...

01:01:12.294 --> 01:01:13.921
This...

01:01:14.129 --> 01:01:15.221
Congratulations, kid.

01:01:15.422 --> 01:01:17.845
You've outdone yourself.
You've reinvented the wheel.

01:01:18.049 --> 01:01:22.600
I'll recommend to the board that we
proceed immediately and that the, uh...

01:01:22.804 --> 01:01:24.852
And that the, uh...

01:01:25.682 --> 01:01:28.561
...dingus be mass-produced
with all deliberate speed.

01:01:28.768 --> 01:01:30.862
Although, you realize...

01:01:31.062 --> 01:01:33.064
...of course...

01:01:35.567 --> 01:01:37.240
...as president...

01:01:37.444 --> 01:01:40.197
...the ultimate decision is yours.

01:01:40.405 --> 01:01:42.499
Oh. I'm for it.

01:01:46.536 --> 01:01:48.914
[BELL RINGING]

01:02:29.287 --> 01:02:31.790
MAN 1:
We'll call it the Flying Doughnut!

01:02:31.998 --> 01:02:32.965
MAN 2:
The Dancing Dingus!

01:02:33.166 --> 01:02:34.463
MAN 1:
The Belly-Go-Round.

01:02:34.668 --> 01:02:35.635
MAN 2:
The Swingerina!

01:02:35.835 --> 01:02:39.135
MAN 1: The Wacky Circumference!
MAN 2: Uncle Midriff!

01:03:10.078 --> 01:03:11.751
MAN 1: We need something short!
MAN 2: Sharp!

01:03:11.955 --> 01:03:13.502
MAN 1: Snappy!
MAN 2: With a little jazz!

01:03:13.707 --> 01:03:14.833
MAN 1:
The Shazzammeter!

01:03:15.041 --> 01:03:16.042
MAN 2:
The Hipster!

01:03:16.251 --> 01:03:17.594
MAN 1:
The Daddy-O!

01:03:20.839 --> 01:03:22.682
[BELL RINGING]

01:03:58.918 --> 01:04:00.636
MAN 1: The Hoopsucker.
MAN 2: The Hudswinger.

01:04:00.837 --> 01:04:04.216
MAN 1: The Hoopsucker!
MAN 2: The Hudswinger!

01:04:25.445 --> 01:04:28.073
MAN 1: The Hoopsucker!
MAN 2: The Hudswinger!

01:04:28.281 --> 01:04:30.079
MAN 1: The Hoopsucker!
MAN 2: The Hudswinger!

01:04:30.283 --> 01:04:33.787
MAN 3: Fellas!
MAN 2: You got something?

01:04:33.995 --> 01:04:35.087
MAN 1:
You got something?

01:04:35.288 --> 01:04:38.258
MAN 3:
Fella, I got something!

01:04:49.969 --> 01:04:51.471
[WHISTLES]

01:04:52.013 --> 01:04:53.014
Ladies.

01:06:19.726 --> 01:06:21.319
[SCHOOL BELL RINGS]

01:06:21.519 --> 01:06:23.487
[ALL CHEERING]

01:07:15.156 --> 01:07:17.124
[ALL CHEERING]

01:07:25.583 --> 01:07:27.301
Wow.

01:07:41.975 --> 01:07:43.773
Norville!

01:07:50.191 --> 01:07:54.617
NEWSCASTER [OVER TV]:
<i>Rockwell News presents,</i> Tidbits of Time.

01:07:54.821 --> 01:07:57.620
<i>World news in pictures,</i>
<i>we kid you not.</i>

01:07:57.824 --> 01:08:01.454
<i>As Old Man 1958</i>
<i>hobbles towards his finish...</i>

01:08:01.661 --> 01:08:04.130
<i>...Barnes is the name</i>
<i>on every American lip.</i>

01:08:04.330 --> 01:08:07.675
<i>Norville Barnes, young president</i>
<i>of Hudsucker Industries...</i>

01:08:07.875 --> 01:08:11.755
<i>...a boy bred in the heartland,</i>
<i>but now the toast of New York.</i>

01:08:11.963 --> 01:08:15.308
<i>Barnes is the brainy inventor</i>
<i>of America's craziest craze:</i>

01:08:15.508 --> 01:08:16.850
<i>The Hula-Hoop!</i>

01:08:17.051 --> 01:08:20.475
<i>Reaping huge profits for his company</i>
<i>and winning the hearts...</i>

01:08:20.680 --> 01:08:23.774
<i>...and hips of every youngster</i>
<i>in America!</i>

01:08:23.975 --> 01:08:26.569
<i>Woo-ho. Did I say youngster?</i>

01:08:26.769 --> 01:08:30.069
<i>Here's Mom taking a break</i>
<i>from her household chores...</i>

01:08:30.273 --> 01:08:33.823
<i>...and even Dad is swinging</i>
<i>into the act!</i>

01:08:34.694 --> 01:08:36.492
<i>Cards, letters, congratulations...</i>

01:08:36.696 --> 01:08:39.666
<i>...come pouring</i>
<i>in from Kankakee to Petaluma...</i>

01:08:39.866 --> 01:08:42.961
<i>...including one very special</i>
<i>long-distance call.</i>

01:08:43.161 --> 01:08:45.880
He's on! He's on the line!

01:08:46.038 --> 01:08:48.292
[ALL CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

01:08:51.544 --> 01:08:52.670
- Hello?
EISENHOWER: <i>Hello, Norville.</i>

01:08:52.879 --> 01:08:54.721
<i>- This is the President.</i>
- Oh, my God, sir.

01:08:54.921 --> 01:08:57.845
<i>I just wanted to congratulate you.</i>
<i>I'm very proud of you.</i>

01:08:58.051 --> 01:09:01.270
- Oh, my God, sir.
<i>- Mrs. Eisenhower is very proud of you.</i>

01:09:01.470 --> 01:09:04.441
<i>The American people</i>
<i>are very proud of you.</i>

01:09:05.015 --> 01:09:06.939
[ALL CHATTERING]

01:09:09.937 --> 01:09:14.113
REPORTER: Mr. Barnes, how'd you come
up with the idea for the Hula-Hoop?

01:09:14.317 --> 01:09:16.035
It was no great idea, really.

01:09:16.234 --> 01:09:18.738
A thing like this takes a whole company
to put together.

01:09:18.946 --> 01:09:20.538
I'm grateful for the opportunity.

01:09:20.740 --> 01:09:23.459
Did you have any idea
there'd be such a huge response?

01:09:23.660 --> 01:09:26.913
Frankly, I don't think anybody
expected this much hoopla.

01:09:27.080 --> 01:09:28.332
[ALL LAUGH]

01:09:28.538 --> 01:09:31.964
"Hoopla on the Hula-Hoop."
Can we quote you on that, Mr. Barnes?

01:09:32.167 --> 01:09:33.215
Sure, I guess.

01:09:33.419 --> 01:09:36.639
Mr. Barnes, will you give yourself a nice,
fat raise?

01:09:36.839 --> 01:09:37.840
[ALL CHUCKLE]

01:09:38.049 --> 01:09:39.517
NORVILLE:
Come on, you guys.

01:09:46.224 --> 01:09:49.398
ANNOUNCER 1: <i>What scientific principle</i>
<i>explains the mind-bending motion...</i>

01:09:49.602 --> 01:09:51.399
<i>...of this whipping wheel of wonder?</i>

01:09:51.604 --> 01:09:53.606
The dingus is quite simple, really.

01:09:53.814 --> 01:09:55.533
It operates on the same principles...

01:09:55.733 --> 01:09:58.031
...that keep the Earth spinning
around the sun...

01:09:58.236 --> 01:10:00.830
...and that keeps you
from flying off the Earth...

01:10:01.030 --> 01:10:02.703
...into the cold reaches of space...

01:10:02.907 --> 01:10:05.205
...where you would die
like a miserable swine.

01:10:05.410 --> 01:10:07.788
Yes, the principle is the same...

01:10:07.995 --> 01:10:12.796
...except for the piece of grit
they put in to make the experience...

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:14.377
...more pleasant.

01:10:14.585 --> 01:10:16.883
ANNOUNCER 2:
<i>Yes, it's Hula-Hula everywhere!</i>

01:10:17.088 --> 01:10:19.591
<i>From the parties of the Park Avenue</i>
<i>smart set...</i>

01:10:23.261 --> 01:10:26.856
<i>...to sweethearts who want to be married</i>
<i>in the swing of things.</i>

01:10:29.767 --> 01:10:32.145
Mr. Barnes, did the board
consider you an idea man...

01:10:32.353 --> 01:10:34.481
...when they promoted you
from the mailroom?

01:10:34.689 --> 01:10:38.284
I guess so, I don't think they promoted me
because they thought I was a schmo.

01:10:38.484 --> 01:10:41.237
Mr. Barnes, what's the next big idea
for you and Hudsucker?

01:10:41.446 --> 01:10:42.447
NORVILLE:
Jesus, I don't know.

01:10:42.655 --> 01:10:45.033
An idea like this sweet baby
doesn't just come overnight.

01:10:45.241 --> 01:10:49.166
Although, I'll tell you one thing,
I certainly didn't expect all this hoopla.

01:10:49.370 --> 01:10:50.337
[CHUCKLES]

01:10:50.538 --> 01:10:51.505
You can quote me on that.

01:10:58.963 --> 01:11:01.807
REPORTER: <i>Rumpus Magazine</i>
has called you the most eligible bachelor.

01:11:02.008 --> 01:11:04.978
And society pages have been linking you
with fashion model Za-Za.

01:11:05.178 --> 01:11:07.647
- You care to comment?
- There's no truth to the rumors.

01:11:07.847 --> 01:11:10.396
We're just dear friends.
Isn't that right, Za-Za?

01:11:12.310 --> 01:11:13.903
[GROWLS]
Wow.

01:11:14.103 --> 01:11:15.320
REPORTERS:
Ooh.

01:11:16.189 --> 01:11:19.489
Whoa. How do you respond to the charges
that you're out of ideas?

01:11:19.692 --> 01:11:21.319
Has Norville Barnes run dry?

01:11:21.527 --> 01:11:25.373
Not at all. Just this week I came up
with several new sweet ideas.

01:11:25.573 --> 01:11:30.079
A larger model Hula-Hoop for the portly,
a battery option for the lazy or spastic.

01:11:30.286 --> 01:11:32.835
A model with extra sand
for the hard-of-hearing.

01:11:33.039 --> 01:11:34.256
I'm earning my keep.

01:11:34.457 --> 01:11:36.801
Speaking of that,
do you expect to get a raise?

01:11:37.001 --> 01:11:41.347
By anyone's account, I single-handedly
have saved Hudsucker Industries.

01:11:41.547 --> 01:11:43.515
Our stock is worth more now than ever.

01:11:43.716 --> 01:11:46.435
Yes, I expect to be compensated for that.

01:12:00.233 --> 01:12:02.406
[SOBBING]

01:12:05.947 --> 01:12:10.168
- Pull yourself together, man.
- Nobody told me!

01:12:10.368 --> 01:12:12.996
You sold all our stock?

01:12:13.204 --> 01:12:14.421
We dumped the whole load.

01:12:14.622 --> 01:12:17.592
I had 20,000 shares!

01:12:17.792 --> 01:12:19.510
I'd be a millionaire now.

01:12:19.710 --> 01:12:22.213
MUSSBURGER:
Sure. We'd all be millionaires.

01:12:22.421 --> 01:12:24.048
There's no point in looking back.

01:12:25.341 --> 01:12:28.891
At the time, Stillson thought dumping
our position would panic the market...

01:12:29.095 --> 01:12:31.314
...further depress the stock.

01:12:31.514 --> 01:12:35.064
Then we could buy it back and more,
of course, once it got cheap.

01:12:35.268 --> 01:12:39.114
Cheap? It's never been more valuable!

01:12:40.273 --> 01:12:43.777
And I'm ruined. Ruined!

01:12:48.739 --> 01:12:49.740
Addison.

01:12:50.491 --> 01:12:54.086
I'm getting off this merry-go-round!

01:12:54.287 --> 01:12:56.085
MAN:
Myron.

01:13:03.880 --> 01:13:05.052
Plexiglas.

01:13:05.631 --> 01:13:07.599
Had it installed last week.

01:13:17.643 --> 01:13:18.644
Myron?

01:13:18.853 --> 01:13:23.984
All right, so the kid caught a wave.

01:13:24.692 --> 01:13:28.663
Right now, he and his dingus are on top.

01:13:28.863 --> 01:13:31.036
Well, this too shall pass.

01:13:31.490 --> 01:13:34.994
Myrtle J. Mussburger
did not raise her boy to go...

01:13:35.202 --> 01:13:37.751
...knock-kneed
at the first sign of adversity.

01:13:37.955 --> 01:13:41.550
I say, we made this chump,
we can break him!

01:13:41.751 --> 01:13:45.301
I say, the higher he climbs,
the harder he drops!

01:13:46.380 --> 01:13:48.098
I say, yes...

01:13:48.299 --> 01:13:51.052
...the kid has a future...

01:13:51.469 --> 01:13:53.142
...and in it...

01:13:53.721 --> 01:13:56.099
...I see shame, dishonor...

01:13:56.307 --> 01:13:59.402
...ignominy, disgrace.

01:13:59.727 --> 01:14:01.855
Sure, sure.

01:14:02.063 --> 01:14:05.658
The music plays, the wheel turns...

01:14:05.858 --> 01:14:08.737
...and our spin ain't over yet.

01:14:08.945 --> 01:14:10.913
[PLAYING CLASSICAL MUSIC]

01:14:32.510 --> 01:14:34.308
For Pete's sakes, Norville!

01:14:34.512 --> 01:14:36.685
NORVILLE:
Oh, Amy, where have you been hiding?

01:14:36.889 --> 01:14:40.109
Do you know what those nincompoops
in the boardroom are doing?

01:14:40.309 --> 01:14:42.152
I wouldn't call them nincompoops.

01:14:42.353 --> 01:14:44.606
They're discharging 80 percent
of the workforce.

01:14:44.814 --> 01:14:47.658
In New York City alone,
that means 1800 people out of work!

01:14:47.858 --> 01:14:49.451
People with wives, children and families!

01:14:49.652 --> 01:14:52.701
Oh, yes, we're pruning away
some of the dead wood.

01:14:52.905 --> 01:14:56.250
- You mean you know about this?
- Know about it? Sure.

01:14:56.450 --> 01:14:59.420
You think the board would do anything
without my authorization?

01:14:59.620 --> 01:15:01.213
It was my idea from the start.

01:15:01.414 --> 01:15:02.711
- Your...
- Sure, it was.

01:15:02.915 --> 01:15:05.543
We're in a period of transition here.
Things have slowed.

01:15:05.751 --> 01:15:08.254
You're being awfully kind to yourself,
Norville Barnes.

01:15:08.462 --> 01:15:12.057
You've slowed down, sitting up
here like a sultan, not doing a lick of work.

01:15:12.258 --> 01:15:14.727
You know ideas
are the lifeblood of industry...

01:15:14.927 --> 01:15:17.225
...and you haven't come up with one since
the Hoop.

01:15:17.430 --> 01:15:20.024
You've forgotten what made your ideas
exciting to you.

01:15:20.224 --> 01:15:22.477
If it wasn't for the fame, wealth,
the adulation...

01:15:22.685 --> 01:15:24.062
Would you get out of here?

01:15:24.270 --> 01:15:27.399
You too, sisters, move it. Out, out, out!

01:15:28.399 --> 01:15:31.403
I've been watching you, even though
you've been avoiding me.

01:15:31.610 --> 01:15:32.577
AMY:
Shut up!

01:15:32.778 --> 01:15:35.031
Don't think I haven't noticed
how you've changed.

01:15:35.239 --> 01:15:36.912
I used to think you were a swell guy.

01:15:37.116 --> 01:15:38.914
I thought you were an imbecile.

01:15:39.118 --> 01:15:40.119
- Amy, I'm...
- Shut up!

01:15:40.327 --> 01:15:43.627
Then I figured out you were a swell guy.
A little slow, but a swell guy.

01:15:43.831 --> 01:15:47.176
Maybe you're not so slow, oh,
but you're not so swell either.

01:15:47.376 --> 01:15:49.754
Looks like you're an imbecile,
after all. Shut up!

01:15:49.962 --> 01:15:53.637
You haven't talked to me for a week
and now I'm going to say my piece.

01:15:53.841 --> 01:15:56.594
Look, I've never been...

01:15:56.802 --> 01:15:59.601
...dumped by a fella before,
and that hurts...

01:15:59.805 --> 01:16:02.433
...but what really hurts is watching you
outrun your soul!

01:16:02.641 --> 01:16:05.269
Chasing after money and ease
and the respect of a board...

01:16:05.478 --> 01:16:07.856
...that wouldn't give you the time
of day if you...

01:16:08.064 --> 01:16:10.613
- If you...
- Worked in a watch factory?

01:16:10.816 --> 01:16:12.113
[CHUCKLES]

01:16:12.318 --> 01:16:14.036
Shut up! Exactly.

01:16:14.779 --> 01:16:18.454
Norville, don't you remember
how you used to feel about the Hoop?

01:16:18.657 --> 01:16:22.412
You told me you'd gonna bring a smile
to the hips of everyone in America...

01:16:22.620 --> 01:16:24.622
...regardless of race, creed or color.

01:16:24.830 --> 01:16:28.130
Finally, there'd be a thingamajig
that would bring everyone together...

01:16:28.334 --> 01:16:30.962
...even if it kept them apart spatially.

01:16:31.170 --> 01:16:33.969
"You know, for kids."

01:16:34.757 --> 01:16:38.307
Your words, Norville, not mine.

01:16:39.178 --> 01:16:41.055
I used to love Norville Barnes.

01:16:41.889 --> 01:16:44.142
Yes, love him...

01:16:44.350 --> 01:16:48.025
...when he was just a swell kid
with hot ideas who was in over his head.

01:16:48.229 --> 01:16:50.152
Now your head's too big to be in over!

01:16:50.356 --> 01:16:52.825
MAN: Hey.
- Consider this my resignation.

01:16:53.275 --> 01:16:54.276
[GROANS]

01:16:54.485 --> 01:16:56.112
Effective immediately!

01:16:57.696 --> 01:16:59.414
[DOOR SLAMS]

01:18:15.941 --> 01:18:18.535
BUZZ:
<i>Buddy, buddy.</i>

01:18:18.736 --> 01:18:20.909
Buddy.

01:18:21.113 --> 01:18:23.912
Buddy. Buddy, say, buddy.

01:18:25.618 --> 01:18:27.461
Buddy, say, buddy.

01:18:27.995 --> 01:18:31.374
Uh... Huh?

01:18:31.582 --> 01:18:33.255
Buddy. You busy?

01:18:33.792 --> 01:18:34.793
Huh?

01:18:35.002 --> 01:18:38.222
Looks like you nodded off there, buddy.
Say, you got a minute?

01:18:40.633 --> 01:18:41.930
Buzz?

01:18:42.134 --> 01:18:43.431
Is this important?

01:18:43.636 --> 01:18:46.765
I think so. It's this little idea
I've been working on.

01:18:46.972 --> 01:18:49.441
You see, I don't intend
to be an elevator boy forever.

01:18:49.642 --> 01:18:51.110
Take a look at this sweet baby!

01:18:51.310 --> 01:18:53.608
Get it? Incredibly convenient, isn't it?

01:18:53.812 --> 01:18:55.280
You know, for drinks?

01:18:55.481 --> 01:18:57.700
This is how it works.
It's got these ridges...

01:18:57.900 --> 01:18:59.618
...on the side that give it
its whammy.

01:18:59.818 --> 01:19:03.368
See, you don't have to drink like this
anymore. You can drink like this.

01:19:03.572 --> 01:19:06.075
I call it the Buzz-Sucker.
You get it, buddy?

01:19:06.283 --> 01:19:09.503
People are dying for this
and we won't have to charge an arm an...

01:19:09.703 --> 01:19:11.125
Wait a minute.

01:19:11.330 --> 01:19:13.128
Shh.

01:19:26.262 --> 01:19:27.809
This...

01:19:30.099 --> 01:19:31.271
...is worthless!

01:19:31.475 --> 01:19:33.068
Huh? But, buddy...

01:19:33.269 --> 01:19:35.271
This is the most idiotic thing
I've ever seen.

01:19:35.479 --> 01:19:36.480
Yeah, but, buddy...

01:19:36.689 --> 01:19:38.737
Nobody wants a harebrained product
like this.

01:19:38.941 --> 01:19:42.115
You see, Buzz,
it lacks the creative spark...

01:19:42.319 --> 01:19:45.573
...the unalloyed genius
that made something like, say...

01:19:45.781 --> 01:19:47.909
...the, uh, Hula-Hoop such a success.

01:19:48.117 --> 01:19:50.370
What do you mean barging in
and taking up my time?

01:19:50.577 --> 01:19:52.124
I've got a company to run here!

01:19:52.329 --> 01:19:53.546
[LAUGHS]

01:19:53.747 --> 01:19:55.499
- But, buddy...
- I can't have every deadbeat...

01:19:55.708 --> 01:19:58.712
...on the payroll pestering me
with their idiotic brainwaves.

01:19:58.919 --> 01:20:00.341
I'm sorry, buddy.

01:20:00.546 --> 01:20:02.924
- An example must be made.
- What do you mean, buddy?

01:20:04.633 --> 01:20:06.351
You're fired.

01:20:06.552 --> 01:20:08.646
Is that plain enough for you, buster?

01:20:08.929 --> 01:20:10.931
[SOBBING]

01:20:13.892 --> 01:20:15.439
Oh, buddy!

01:20:16.186 --> 01:20:18.188
And don't call me "buddy."

01:20:18.397 --> 01:20:22.868
Oh, please, sir!
This job running the elevator, it's all I got!

01:20:23.068 --> 01:20:24.786
Uh, it's okay if you don't like it.

01:20:24.987 --> 01:20:28.366
Just let me keep my job,
I'm praying to you.

01:20:28.574 --> 01:20:32.920
Get out of my office! Get up! Up!

01:20:33.120 --> 01:20:35.919
We don't crawl here
at Hudsucker Industries!

01:20:37.416 --> 01:20:40.886
BUZZ:
I'm sorry, sir! I'm sorry!

01:20:42.087 --> 01:20:44.055
[BUZZ CONTINUES SOBBING]

01:20:54.350 --> 01:20:56.944
MUSSBURGER:
Thank you, Aloysius.

01:21:00.898 --> 01:21:03.196
This is...

01:21:04.026 --> 01:21:05.744
...useful.

01:21:19.917 --> 01:21:21.419
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

01:21:23.295 --> 01:21:28.017
Sorry I'm late, Sid.
That back nine at Riverdale's really murder.

01:21:28.801 --> 01:21:31.930
MUSSBURGER:
It's a tough course. A real lollapalooza.

01:21:33.138 --> 01:21:34.230
Sit down, son.

01:21:37.643 --> 01:21:42.615
I thought the boardroom would be
a swell place to chat undisturbed.

01:21:43.023 --> 01:21:47.153
Seems we've got some security
problems here at the Hud.

01:21:47.361 --> 01:21:48.783
You don't say.

01:21:48.987 --> 01:21:51.240
MUSSBURGER:
Ordinarily, I wouldn't bother you with it...

01:21:51.448 --> 01:21:53.621
...but this is embarrassing.

01:21:54.284 --> 01:21:56.412
It concerns you directly.

01:21:56.620 --> 01:21:59.248
- How's that, Sid?
- It's not serious in itself.

01:21:59.915 --> 01:22:03.089
Some elevator boy
that you'd fired came to me...

01:22:03.293 --> 01:22:07.264
...claiming that you'd stolen the idea
for, um, the dingus.

01:22:07.464 --> 01:22:09.432
You'd stolen it from him.

01:22:09.633 --> 01:22:10.976
[MUMBLES]

01:22:12.219 --> 01:22:14.722
- Maybe I was a little rough on him...
- Forget it.

01:22:14.930 --> 01:22:18.230
You don't have to explain to me.
He's a little person. He's nothing.

01:22:18.434 --> 01:22:19.811
Fire whoever you want.

01:22:21.854 --> 01:22:25.984
No, the problem is who you hired.

01:22:26.191 --> 01:22:30.037
That dame. A spy, as it turns out.

01:22:30.237 --> 01:22:33.707
She must have gotten
to that elevator schnook...

01:22:33.907 --> 01:22:37.036
...and her paper is going to town.

01:22:37.244 --> 01:22:42.671
Sure, sure, we tried to kill the story,
but the <i>Argus</i> won't play ball.

01:22:43.208 --> 01:22:46.007
The problem the board
will have is you hired this woman...

01:22:46.211 --> 01:22:48.839
...and you kept her on...

01:22:49.047 --> 01:22:51.846
...while she was making a chump
out of you.

01:22:52.050 --> 01:22:54.599
Serious error in judgment.

01:22:55.387 --> 01:22:57.606
Business is war, kid.

01:22:57.806 --> 01:23:00.855
Take no prisoners,
give no second chances.

01:23:04.313 --> 01:23:06.862
When the board meets
after New Year's...

01:23:07.065 --> 01:23:08.988
...your position...

01:23:11.361 --> 01:23:13.204
Looks like you're finished.

01:23:13.697 --> 01:23:15.290
Washed up.

01:23:19.411 --> 01:23:22.790
Oh, fourteenth hole at Riverdale...

01:23:22.998 --> 01:23:26.969
...some use a mashie,
some use a niblick.

01:23:27.169 --> 01:23:28.762
Niblick.

01:23:28.962 --> 01:23:31.215
You get more loft, more backspin.

01:23:36.428 --> 01:23:37.975
That dame...

01:23:38.805 --> 01:23:41.900
...she got your throat pretty well slit.

01:23:42.100 --> 01:23:44.068
When you're dead, you stay dead.

01:23:45.270 --> 01:23:48.194
You don't believe me,
ask Waring Hudsucker.

01:23:49.858 --> 01:23:54.238
Tough luck, kid.
You had a short climb up.

01:23:54.655 --> 01:23:56.783
It's a long way down.

01:24:07.417 --> 01:24:09.419
AMY: Stolen hoop idea from...
You can't print that!

01:24:09.628 --> 01:24:10.629
AL:
We are printing it!

01:24:10.837 --> 01:24:12.965
She hits the streets this evening.

01:24:13.173 --> 01:24:15.050
And she's dynamite!

01:24:15.259 --> 01:24:16.431
But, AI, it's the bunk!

01:24:16.635 --> 01:24:19.184
Norville showed me his design
the, uh, day I met him.

01:24:19.388 --> 01:24:22.232
Buzz couldn't have invented it.
Look at him, he's an imbecile.

01:24:22.432 --> 01:24:24.855
Aren't you a broken record?
Gunderson did design it.

01:24:25.060 --> 01:24:26.437
Apparently, he's a prodigy.

01:24:26.645 --> 01:24:28.864
- Says who?
- You're not the only one with sources.

01:24:29.064 --> 01:24:31.567
Smith has a source on the Hud board.
Very hush-hush.

01:24:31.775 --> 01:24:34.119
Yeah. I bet his initials
are Sidney J. Mussburger.

01:24:34.319 --> 01:24:37.198
You lost it, Amy.
You gone soft, by the looks of it.

01:24:37.406 --> 01:24:39.079
Soft on the dummy from Dubuque.

01:24:40.117 --> 01:24:41.369
- Muncie.
AL: Whatever!

01:24:41.577 --> 01:24:45.377
This story's hot and you're no longer on
top of it. It's the scoop of the century!

01:24:45.581 --> 01:24:47.675
The other papers
won't have this till tomorrow!

01:24:47.874 --> 01:24:51.629
They'll be choking on our dust
come morning.

01:24:51.837 --> 01:24:55.307
You're fools, both of you!
You're being used, don't you see, ugh?

01:24:55.507 --> 01:24:58.681
Take a break. You worked hard
on this story. You broke it for us.

01:24:58.885 --> 01:25:01.934
But it's passed you by
and Smith's taking up the slack.

01:25:02.973 --> 01:25:06.318
Tsk, oh, you want slack,
I'll give you slack!

01:25:06.518 --> 01:25:10.318
You're not putting me out to pasture!
I quit! Consider this my resignation!

01:25:10.522 --> 01:25:11.899
[BANGS]

01:25:12.107 --> 01:25:14.326
Effective immediately!

01:25:16.570 --> 01:25:18.413
Soft.

01:25:27.039 --> 01:25:28.791
BRONFENBRENNER [OVER SPEAKER]:
<i>So tell me...</i>

01:25:28.999 --> 01:25:31.752
<i>...why do you feel</i>
<i>this woman betrayed you?</i>

01:25:31.960 --> 01:25:35.339
<i>Tsk, oh, what's the difference?</i>

01:25:35.547 --> 01:25:38.300
<i>The whole world,</i>
<i>it seems, is against you?</i>

01:25:38.508 --> 01:25:39.634
<i>I don't know.</i>

01:25:39.843 --> 01:25:41.686
Und <i>the elevator boy...</i>

01:25:41.887 --> 01:25:45.061
<i>...Buzz, he too works against you?</i>

01:25:45.265 --> 01:25:46.983
NORVILLE:
<i>Well, yeah.</i>

01:25:47.184 --> 01:25:48.356
Classic.

01:25:48.560 --> 01:25:51.780
Patient displayed listlessness,
apathy, gloomy indifference...

01:25:51.980 --> 01:25:54.028
<i>...und</i> was blue <i>und</i> mopey.

01:25:54.232 --> 01:25:57.452
When asked what the Rorschach stains
represented, patient replied:

01:25:57.944 --> 01:26:02.666
"Nothing much. I don't know.
Just a blotch. Sure beats me."

01:26:02.866 --> 01:26:06.461
Patient shows no ambition,
no get-up-and-go, no vim.

01:26:06.662 --> 01:26:09.165
He is riding the grand loopen-ze-loop...

01:26:09.373 --> 01:26:12.217
...that goes from the height
of delusional gaiety...

01:26:12.417 --> 01:26:14.511
...to the trough of despair.

01:26:14.711 --> 01:26:17.885
He is now near,
but not yet at his lowest point.

01:26:18.090 --> 01:26:23.972
When he reaches bottom, he may erupt
<i>und</i> pose a danger to himself <i>und</i> others.

01:26:24.179 --> 01:26:26.056
MUSSBURGER:
Diagnosis, Dr. Bronfenbrenner?

01:26:26.264 --> 01:26:29.234
Patient is <i>eine</i> manic-depressive
paranoid, type B...

01:26:29.434 --> 01:26:31.311
...with acute schizoid tendencies.

01:26:31.520 --> 01:26:34.524
So patient is...?

01:26:35.273 --> 01:26:37.696
Precisely, nuts!

01:26:38.276 --> 01:26:39.323
Prescription?

01:26:39.528 --> 01:26:44.500
Three things, commitment,
electroconvulsive therapy...

01:26:44.700 --> 01:26:48.170
...maintenance in <i>eine</i> secure facility.

01:26:48.829 --> 01:26:50.752
[ALL APPLAUDING]

01:27:02.968 --> 01:27:05.767
MAN:
Yeah, he's a tall guy. A real mess.

01:27:05.971 --> 01:27:10.351
Yeah, yeah, look, you better get down here.
He says he's a friend of yours.

01:27:10.559 --> 01:27:14.280
He didn't say.
But, man, is he from Squaresville.

01:27:16.440 --> 01:27:18.613
[NORVILLE TALKS INDISTINCTLY]

01:27:18.817 --> 01:27:20.569
[BLOWS HORN]

01:27:22.070 --> 01:27:23.617
NORVILLE:
I want a martini!

01:27:23.822 --> 01:27:26.621
It's New Year's Eve. I deserve a martini.

01:27:26.825 --> 01:27:31.126
- Daddy, it's like I've been telling you. You...
- I thought you served misfits here.

01:27:31.329 --> 01:27:34.128
Yeah, daddy. That's a roger.
But we don't sell alcohol.

01:27:34.332 --> 01:27:36.801
What kind of bar is it,
you can't get a martini?

01:27:37.002 --> 01:27:40.472
It's a juice-and-coffee bar, man,
like I've been telling you.

01:27:40.672 --> 01:27:45.724
- Right. So I want a martini.
- Argh.

01:27:45.927 --> 01:27:49.306
I've had a martini in every bar
all the way down here, heh.

01:27:49.514 --> 01:27:51.983
Martinis are for squares, man.

01:27:53.435 --> 01:27:56.405
What'd you call me,
you beatnik son of a...?

01:27:56.605 --> 01:27:57.606
AMY:
Norville.

01:27:59.608 --> 01:28:00.780
What?

01:28:00.984 --> 01:28:05.410
- Oh-ho, look who's here, Amy Archer...
- Oh, no.

01:28:05.614 --> 01:28:07.787
...Prizeter Pule winner.

01:28:07.991 --> 01:28:10.085
Looking for a nitwit to buy you lunch?

01:28:10.285 --> 01:28:13.960
- Norville, I'm sorry.
- Bar fella, I'd like...

01:28:14.164 --> 01:28:15.165
...a martini, please.

01:28:15.373 --> 01:28:19.003
I tried to tell you so many times, I...

01:28:19.211 --> 01:28:23.216
It's hard to admit
when you've been wrong.

01:28:23.423 --> 01:28:25.050
If you could just...

01:28:25.258 --> 01:28:29.889
...find it in your heart
to give me another chance.

01:28:30.972 --> 01:28:31.973
Ha.

01:28:32.182 --> 01:28:34.435
"You take no prisoners,
give no second chances."

01:28:34.643 --> 01:28:38.022
Please, Norville!
Please give me one more chance!

01:28:38.230 --> 01:28:41.655
And yourself too. We both deserve one.

01:28:41.858 --> 01:28:43.201
Just give us a second chance.

01:28:43.401 --> 01:28:45.369
Together we can fight this thing.

01:28:45.570 --> 01:28:47.993
I know this last story was a lie
and we can prove it.

01:28:48.198 --> 01:28:49.541
You got to release a statement.

01:28:49.741 --> 01:28:53.245
- I can help you write it.
- Oh, what's the difference?

01:28:53.453 --> 01:28:55.626
I'm all washed up.

01:28:55.831 --> 01:28:59.881
Extinct. <i>Homo sapiens sapicus.</i>

01:29:00.085 --> 01:29:01.052
[HICCUPPING]

01:29:01.253 --> 01:29:05.679
Well, heh, that just about does it.

01:29:05.882 --> 01:29:09.512
I've seen Norville Barnes,
the young man in a big hurry...

01:29:09.719 --> 01:29:13.223
...and I've seen Norville Barnes,
the self-important heel.

01:29:13.431 --> 01:29:16.560
But I've never seen Norville Barnes,
the quitter...

01:29:17.269 --> 01:29:19.397
...and I don't like it.

01:29:20.438 --> 01:29:22.406
Fight on.

01:29:22.607 --> 01:29:26.362
Fight on, dear old Muncie.

01:29:27.070 --> 01:29:31.541
Fight on. Hoist the gold and blue.

01:29:31.741 --> 01:29:35.462
You'll be tattered, torn and hurting.

01:29:35.662 --> 01:29:40.418
Once the Munce is done with you.

01:29:41.626 --> 01:29:44.846
Go, Eagles.

01:29:46.923 --> 01:29:49.392
You can't surrender, Norville.
Remember.

01:29:50.760 --> 01:29:55.766
[SINGING] <i>Fight on, Fight on</i>
<i>Dear old Muncie</i>

01:29:55.974 --> 01:29:56.975
[SOBBING]

01:29:57.183 --> 01:30:02.360
<i>Fight on</i>
<i>Hoist the gold and blue</i>

01:30:03.315 --> 01:30:07.115
<i>You'll be tattered, torn and hurting</i>

01:30:08.945 --> 01:30:12.916
You lied to me. How could you lie to me?

01:30:14.743 --> 01:30:18.418
You, a Muncie girl.

01:30:19.706 --> 01:30:22.425
But, Norville, I...

01:30:22.626 --> 01:30:28.975
When you're dead, you stay dead.
Just ask Waring Hudsucker!

01:30:30.216 --> 01:30:32.469
Oh, Norville.

01:30:32.677 --> 01:30:34.725
[SOBS]

01:30:35.263 --> 01:30:38.642
NEWSBOY:
Extra, extra! New Year's Eve edition!

01:30:38.850 --> 01:30:41.228
Barnes' brain caught red-handed!

01:30:41.436 --> 01:30:43.029
Ideas ersatz!

01:30:43.229 --> 01:30:46.153
Man from Muncie a moron after all!

01:30:46.358 --> 01:30:48.452
Read all about it!

01:30:48.652 --> 01:30:52.998
New Year's Eve edition!
Man from Muncie a moron after all!

01:30:53.198 --> 01:30:55.166
You're not so slow,
but you're not so swell.

01:30:55.367 --> 01:30:57.495
And it looks like
you're an imbecile after all.

01:30:57.702 --> 01:31:00.831
Sure, sure.
But your friends called you dope?

01:31:01.039 --> 01:31:03.212
Dipstick? Lamebrain? Schmo?

01:31:03.416 --> 01:31:06.420
Please, buddy, running the elevator,
it's all I got.

01:31:06.628 --> 01:31:08.596
EISENHOWER:
<i>Norville, you let me down.</i>

01:31:08.797 --> 01:31:13.098
<i>You let Mrs. Eisenhower down.</i>
<i>You let the American people down.</i>

01:31:13.301 --> 01:31:15.679
- And when you're dead, you stay dead.
AMY: Ha-ha-ha.

01:31:15.887 --> 01:31:19.187
You stay dead, you stay dead.
Sure, sure.

01:31:19.391 --> 01:31:22.440
The kid is screwy, it's official.

01:31:23.061 --> 01:31:26.190
The barred-window boys
are out looking for him now.

01:31:26.398 --> 01:31:28.366
We'll see how Wall Street
likes the news...

01:31:28.566 --> 01:31:31.820
...that the president of Hudsucker
is headed for the booby hatch.

01:31:32.028 --> 01:31:36.329
Heh, when Doc Bronfenbrenner
gets through with him...

01:31:36.533 --> 01:31:38.535
...he'll need diapers and a dribble cup.

01:31:38.743 --> 01:31:39.744
[ALL CHUCKLE]

01:31:39.953 --> 01:31:42.376
Well, if that's all...

01:31:42.580 --> 01:31:45.459
ALL:
Long live the Hud!

01:31:47.627 --> 01:31:49.595
[UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING IN DISTANCE]

01:31:53.425 --> 01:31:54.392
[ALL GRUNT]

01:31:54.592 --> 01:31:57.971
Watch where you're... Hiya, buddy!

01:31:58.179 --> 01:32:00.307
- Buzz?
- Out on the town, huh? Guess what?

01:32:00.515 --> 01:32:05.487
Sid says I can have my old job back.
I deserve a second chance, he says.

01:32:05.687 --> 01:32:08.987
- Huh? He did?
- Turns out he's not such a bad guy after all.

01:32:09.190 --> 01:32:10.863
- Ha, ha.
- Buzz, that's wonderful.

